<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Tries To Help Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Government crackdowns on immigration and the  
changing face of America's workforce have prompted the AFL-CIO to 
renew efforts to reach out to immigrant workers, union officials 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is planning four public forums, in Atlanta, Chicago,  
Los Angeles and New York, to hear from immigrant workers about 
working conditions and efforts to unionize. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigrants have long been exploited on the job but rarely speak  
out for fear of being fired or deported, said Clayola Brown, vice 
president of the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile 
Employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many horror stories out there. We truly don't  
know the depth because there is so much fear,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to union figures, one in 10 U.S. workers was born  
outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Daisy Cabrera, 26, who has worked as a janitor for union and  
non-union companies, said her non-union employer did not provide 
overtime or health benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed the job. If I protested, I'd get fired,'' she said.  
``With the union, we have control of our work load. When we were 
not unionized, they dumped work on us and we were expected to do 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO officials said the effort to reach immigrants comes as  
the Immigration and Naturalization Service is cracking down on 
undocumented workers in labor-intensive industries, such as 
meatpacking. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Operation Vanguard, the INS has subpoenaed employee  
records at several Midwest plants to verify workers' immigration 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	While the method has prompted questions about invasion of  
privacy and concerns about labor shortages, the INS says it is less 
disruptive than workplace raids. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
