<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Rivals Attack Bush's Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Conservative candidates vying for the  
Republican presidential nomination criticized front-runner George 
W. Bush on Saturday for ``beating up on the conservatives'' and 
distancing himself from core GOP values. 
</P>
<P>
	``My concern with Mr. Bush is what he's saying out there on the  
campaign trail,'' Pat Buchanan told about 1,000 people at the 
National Federation of Republican Assemblies convention. ``He's 
been beating up on the conservatives. He's been pandering to the 
media by beating up on us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan and fellow conservatives Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes and  
Alan Keyes preached tax reform, anti-abortion policy and family 
values to members of the public and 320 convention delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	A non-binding straw poll was won by Forbes, who received 380 of  
829 votes, or 45.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm absolutely delighted,'' Forbes said. ``I think it shows  
conservatives are rallying to my candidacy. This is going to become 
a race similar to 1980, where the conservatives fought the 
outsiders. The outsiders won in '80, and we're going do it again 
next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan came in second with 172 votes, or 20.8 percent,  
followed by Keyes with 149 votes and Bauer with 86 votes. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFRA, founded in 1996, is a grass-roots conservative  
organization that bills itself as ``the Republican wing of the 
Republican Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the event, each candidate mentioned the Texas governor  
directly, criticizing Bush's stance on big government and his 
reluctance to require that all judge appointees oppose abortion 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who skipped the convention along with GOP hopefuls John  
McCain, Elizabeth Dole and Orrin Hatch, received 35 votes. McCain 
and Dole received three each, and Hatch none. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said earlier in the week that Republicans were too often  
pessimistic and confused limited government with ``a disdain for 
government itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This governor in Texas is the pessimist in the race. He is  
running as a Bush Republican and I will proudly run as a Reagan 
Republican,'' Bauer said to a chorus of cheers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer called Bush's comments ``a surrender'' to expansive  
government and a departure from conservative values. 
</P>
<P>
	``That obviously hit nerves with the Republican Party. Those are  
two issues that Republicans care a great deal about,'' he said. 
``If the governor keeps making speeches like that it's going to 
guarantee that we're going to have an open race that's going to go 
all the way to the convention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spent Saturday in Springfield, Mo., at a fund-raiser and  
cookout for Republican Rep. Roy Blunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day, Forbes, Bauer and Sen. Hatch traveled to Des  
Moines, Iowa, to stress their anti-abortion credentials before a 
gathering of the Iowa Right to Life convention. 
</P>
<P>
	All told the audience of about 250 that they would never abandon  
social issues such as abortion and euthanasia, and Forbes and Bauer 
said they would appoint only judges opposed to abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, took a  
measured swipe at Bush's father, former President Bush, for his 
judicial appointments. ``To be honest with you, the most liberal 
pro-abortion judge on the Supreme Court was appointed by our last 
Republican president,'' he said in a reference to Justice David 
Souter. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Kansas City convention, demands for comprehensive tax  
reform and anti-abortion Supreme Court justices drew wild cheers. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, while pushing his proposed 17 percent flat tax, called  
for elimination of all individual taxes such as estate taxes, or as 
he put it, ``taxation without respiration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes equated the tax reform movement to fighting slavery, and  
called for the abolition of the personal income tax. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people go out and work for the money, the people ought to  
be the ones in control of the management of that money,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan both entered and left the stage to a chanting chorus of  
``stay, Pat, stay.'' Earlier this week, Buchanan said he was 
``leaning toward'' leaving the Republican Party to seek the Reform 
Party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan made no mention of the Reform Party during his  
20-minute speech. He canceled a news conference scheduled by the 
NFRA. His political director, Tim Haley, said Buchanan had been ill 
and had never promised to meet with reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFRA delegates from 33 states will vote Sunday afternoon on  
one candidate the organization can back for the Republican 
presidential nomination. All candidates are on the ballot, and the 
group's bylaws require a two-thirds majority to earn NFRA backing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
