<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accidents Hits Heart of Japan Nukes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- Fumiko Kawasaki was just finishing lunch  
when firemen rushed into her farm supplies store and told her to 
evacuate. They didn't say why, and she didn't want to ask. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew something was up because police were already sealing  
off the area,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the nuclear fuel processing plant across the street, workers  
had ignored safety procedures -- possibly with the tacit approval of 
cost-conscious supervisors -- and mixed up a batch of uranium so 
volatile it sent a potent burst of radiation into the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	By nightfall, the mix went critical, simmering into a  
self-sustaining nuclear reaction. Three plant employees were 
hospitalized with potentially fatal doses of radiation. Hundreds of 
thousands of people holed up indoors awaiting word that it was safe 
to venture outside again. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Japan's most serious nuclear accident, probably rating a  
five on the scale used by the International Atomic Energy 
Commission -- equal to the Three Mile Island accident of 1979. 
Chernobyl was a seven. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have grown up with nuclear power,'' Kawasaki said as she  
sipped coffee made with bottled water -- officials told her not to 
use the well just yet. ``But this accident made us realize how 
little we really know about what is going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of her neighbors was less sanguine.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are deeply involved in the nuclear industry here,'' said  
Hiroko Gocho, a pharmacist who was working about a half mile from 
the processing plant when the radiation leaked. ``We trusted them, 
and they betrayed our trust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	To even the most casual visitor, it's clear Tokaimura is a  
poster town for Japan's nuclear power program. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's first commercial nuclear reactor, Tokai, was  
completed here in 1966. That reactor was decommissioned last year 
because it was deemed too costly to operate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokai II reactor has been in operation since 1978. Both  
reactors are only about a 15-minute drive from the center of town, 
and a dozen other related facilities for processing, handling or 
studying nuclear materials line the coast to the east and the 
town's western outskirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside town hall a two-story-tall sign declares: ``We oppose  
nuclear weapons; We promote the peaceful use of nuclear power.'' 
The two main roads running through the center of town are Nuclear 
Research Street and Nuclear Power Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Few townspeople openly oppose nuclear power.  
</P>
<P>
	About a third of the work force is employed by the nuclear  
industry, and all benefit from the huge share of tax money the 
plants contribute to the town's coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	And officials always stressed their concern for safety. In case  
of emergency, special intercoms are installed in 10,000 homes in 
the area and public address systems sit atop utility poles in 66 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	But even when the warnings were broadcast two hours after the  
radiation leak Sept. 30, few thought the trouble could be coming 
from the uranium processing plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We assumed it was across town at a reactor,'' Gocho said. ``We  
had no idea they were doing something so dangerous at the plant. It 
looks more like just a little workshop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	A short walk from town hall, the processing plant is surrounded  
by a low fence and trees, and ringed by small farms and mom-and-pop 
shops. 
</P>
<P>
	On the outside, little has changed since the accident, although  
police officers now stand around its perimeter. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, however, the dangers remain.  
</P>
<P>
	JCO, the private company that operates the plant, says it is  
cautiously allowing workers back into the area of the complex where 
the accident occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now you can walk around inside the plant in most places,''  
said spokesman Akira Iwata. ``But we are still considering what to 
do with that section. You can't go in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	JCO, in fact, has no idea what will be done with the  
nondescript, concrete building where the leak occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't make any decision on our own,'' Iwata said. ``We are  
consulting with the Science and Technology Agency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say much of the cleanup problem stems from the fact  
that as a processing plant -- as opposed to a nuclear reactor -- the 
facility was not designed to handle a nuclear chain reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	And, company officials admit, it never would have happened had  
even a modicum of safety procedures been observed. 
</P>
<P>
	JCO officials say the accident happened something like this:  
</P>
<P>
	To speed up their work, workers used a stainless steel bucket to  
mix a uranium compound with nitric acid, bypassing a system of 
mechanized tanks. JCO admits that was not unusual. But this time, 
the workers used 6.5 times more uranium than the safe limit, and 
were mixing uranium of an unusually high grade. 
</P>
<P>
	The first bursts of radiation were detected outside the plant at  
about 10:35 a.m., and a few hours later the uranium mix went 
critical. The chain reaction continued for more than 17 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents got their first warning about two hours after the  
initial burst. That night, everyone within 6 miles of the plant was 
advised to stay indoors. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts now say that after the initial leak, radiation levels in  
the area probably returned to normal quickly. Unlike at Chernobyl, 
there was no explosion and no radioactive material escaped the 
building. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the ramifications spread.  
</P>
<P>
	Police are investigating whether the negligence was part of a  
systematic and illegal attempt by JCO management to cut costs. The 
government is preparing to revoke its operating license, and set 
new standards for the six other processing facilities still in 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Further delays are likely, experts say, despite the government's  
vow to push ahead with plans to build more reactors to produce 
electricity. Already, officials say the Fugen reactor west of Tokyo 
may be shut down because without the Tokaimura facility there is no 
place to store its spent fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	And though Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi visited the site  
personally to demonstrate the danger was gone, prices for area farm 
produce have plummeted. Thousands of worried residents are still 
seeking blood tests and medical checks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody wants to live here anymore,'' said Miwa Sukegawa, a  
housewife and mother of two small children. ``It's just so 
frightening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Yutaka Yoshii watches his steps as he walks around dozens of  
radiation detectors spread out on the floor outside the makeshift 
emergency center where officials are trying to figure out what to 
do about the processing plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The command center is set up at Atom World, a small theme park  
on the edge of the grounds of the Tokai II nuclear reactor. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibitions aimed at children boast of the wonders of nuclear  
power. There is a reactor turbine next to a fountain outside, and 
an Atomic Theater where groups can watch promos for the nuclear 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are no visitors now, only harried experts and nuclear  
power industry employees talking on cell phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally, this would be full of people,'' said Yoshii, who is  
assistant general manager of the Tokaimura offices of Japan Atomic 
Power Co. ``But we had to close it to set up the center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like other industry officials, Yoshii is cautious about  
condemning how the processing plant was run. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to really know the facts before we make judgments,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he acknowledged it will probably color the way the  
Japanese look at nuclear power for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a terrible shame,'' he said. ``Japan needs nuclear  
power. But we must never forget the need for safety, and trust.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
