<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Judges Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton today challenged the Senate to  
act on his nominations of Hispanics to federal judgeships, and said 
partisanship is hindering the progress of minorities in the 
judiciary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am proud that we have succeeded in appointing more Hispanics  
to the federal bench than any administration in history,'' Clinton 
told the Hispanic Leadership Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	He said too many Hispanic nominees are languishing in the  
Senate, waiting for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am deeply dissatisfied with the Senate's partisan handling  
of some of my minority nominees,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated some of the strong language he used earlier in the  
week to denounce the Republican-led Senate for rejecting the 
nomination of Ronnie White, a black judge who had earlier won GOP 
endorsements. The nomination went down on a straight party line 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a disgrace,'' Clinton said bitterly.  
</P>
<P>
	The speech was Clinton's last on a three-day trip that began  
with addresses to labor and gay groups in New York on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	During stops in Canada on Friday, Clinton drew a firm line  
against any U.S. support for an independent Quebec, and said ethnic 
and tribal groups the world over must resist the impulse to declare 
themselves sovereign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must think of how we will live after the shooting stops,  
after the smoke clears,'' Clinton said during a conference in 
Quebec on federalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used his one-day Canadian visit to fine-tune friendly  
relations with the United States' northern neighbor. He and Prime 
Minister Jean Chretien reached an agreement on exchanging defense 
technology, and talked a bit about trade, nuclear proliferation and 
peacekeeping in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not make direct comparisons to Quebec, a French-speaking  
province of 7 million that is frustrated with the Canadian federal 
system and has held two independence referendums. In 1995, it came 
close to voting to split from Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Clinton cited East Timor as an example, saying that  
region now faces tremendous difficulties because it broke away from 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Does that mean they were wrong? No. Under the circumstances  
they faced, they probably made the only decision they could have,'' 
Clinton said. ``But wouldn't it have been better if they could have 
found their religious, their cultural, their ethnic and their 
economic footing in genuine self-government in the framework of a 
larger entity, which would also have supported them economically?'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the federalism conference, Clinton spent about 15 minutes  
with Quebec's separatist premier, Lucien Bouchard. A senior 
administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 
Clinton and Bouchard had ``a friendly, informal chat'' in which 
Bouchard said how much he enjoyed Clinton's speech; the subject of 
sovereignty in Quebec never came up, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, the president helped dedicate a new U.S. Embassy.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
