<HEADLINE> Columbine Victim Parents Expand Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- An attorney for the parents of a student killed at  
Columbine High School said Saturday he plans to expand the family's 
wrongful death lawsuit to include at least one gun manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Geoffrey Fieger of Michigan said that Florida-based Navegar and  
a subsidiary, Intratec, which made the TEC-DC9 semiautomatic pistol 
used during the April 20 attack, likely would be named as 
defendants within two weeks. He said the companies' marketing 
practices were designed to make the weapon attractive to criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt it could be used by legitimate hunters for legitimate  
purposes,'' Fieger said. ``It's marketed as being made of an alloy 
that doesn't carry fingerprints.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fieger represents Michael and Vonda Shoels, whose son Isaiah was  
among 12 students killed by teen-age gunmen Dylan Klebold and Eric 
Harris in their attack on the school. Harris and Klebold also 
killed one teacher before turning their guns on themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoels family spokesman Sam Riddle said Friday that Fieger and  
Colorado co-counsel Jack Beam were heartened by a California 
appeals court decision last week that reinstated a lawsuit against 
Navegar and Intratec. 
</P>
<P>
	That suit involves the TEC-DC9 a gunman used to kill eight  
people and wound six in a San Francisco office building in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shoelses in May sued the parents of Klebold and Harris,  
saying they should have known their sons were amassing a cache of 
guns and bombs to use in the attack. The lawsuit seeks $250 million 
in damages. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
