<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hollywood Park Dropped As NFL Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Days after Los Angeles lost to Houston  
in an effort to win an NFL expansion team, one of the principal 
California bidders abandoned Hollywood Park as a new stadium site. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz said he still wants to bring the  
NFL back to Southern California, but he chose Friday not to 
exercise the option on nearly 100 acres of land at the Inglewood 
racetrack. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just decided it was not economically prudent to exercise  
the option without having the franchise,'' Ovitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	He had until Friday to exercise the option he and partner Ron  
Burkle picked up when Los Angeles billionaire oilman Marvin Davis 
allowed it to lapse. Davis dropped out of bidding a week after 
entering negotiations on Sept. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning the property to Hollywood Park is not a signal Ovitz  
plans to abandon his quest to return the NFL to Los Angeles, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've gone this far. We're not going to stop now,'' he said.  
``We're not backing out of it at all. We just don't want to own the 
real estate in the hopes of somebody moving here. It's not a good 
use of my money or Ron Burkle's, that's all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood Park officials have said they planned to sell the site  
to a non-sports developer if it was not purchased for use as a 
stadium site. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL officials urged Ovitz to purchase the $55 million property  
in his bid to lure an existing team to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams in Phoenix, New Orleans, Buffalo and Minnesota have been  
identified among those that might be interested in moving. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Davis, who took the Raiders out of the Los Angeles Coliseum  
and back to Oakland after the 1994 season, also has indicated he 
might like to return. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston's expansion franchise bid was $1 billion -- $150 million  
higher than offers by either the Los Angeles Coliseum group or the 
one headed by Ovitz at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer, the richest ever for a franchise, came from Houston  
businessman Bob McNair and includes the $700 million franchise 
price and a $310 million stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston will begin play in 2002 in the American Football  
Conference, where the Oilers played before moving to Tennessee 
after the 1996 season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
