<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tipper Gore Asks for Labor Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tipper Gore made an impassioned plea Saturday  
for organized labor to ``stand with Al,'' as backroom wrangling 
continued over an early AFL-CIO endorsement of her husband's 
presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please stand with Al and fight for the change that will give  
our children and our grandchildren the America equal to our best 
possibilities and the highest ideals in each of our hearts,'' the 
vice president's wife asked several thousand workers rallying in 
advance of the AFL-CIO convention that opens here Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO president John Sweeney told affiliated union presidents  
privately Friday that his priority at the convention is to give 
Gore the federation's early endorsement, several labor officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	An endorsement now would give Gore thousands of grass-roots  
mobilizers to help beat back the increasingly strong challenge by 
former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald McEntee, chairman of the labor federation's political  
committee and chief advocate of an early Gore endorsement, said 
Saturday he is confident he has the votes to prevail even though 
some union presidents would rather not rush ahead before their 
members have had a chance to study the candidates' records. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the time, this is the place,'' McEntee said in an  
interview. With all the high-profile speculation about the strength 
of Gore's campaign, he said he did not want this week's convention 
to leave the vice president empty-handed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stakes are high because there's been sort of a big  
spotlight on this,'' McEntee said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the floor of the Los Angeles Convention Center, green-shirted  
members of McEntee's American Federation of State, County and 
Municipal Employees hoisted a dozen or so ``Gore 2000'' campaign 
posters as Mrs. Gore addressed Saturday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Her voice rose as she ran through her husband's record and  
repeated nearly a dozen times the beseeching refrain, ``stand with 
Al.'' Her husband's support for unionized workers goes back for 
decades, to the time he was a congressman from Tennessee, she said. 
``Al's support for labor unions is based on principle, not 
politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	California Gov. Gray Davis weighed in with an offbeat appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would not be standing here if you had not taken a chance on  
me -- this boring, dull fellow dismissed as roadkill and yesterday's 
news,'' Davis said, adding a plea, too, for California Sen. Dianne 
Feinstein, who is up for re-election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I urge you to take that same attitude ... and, please, endorse  
Dianne Feinstein and Al Gore at some point during your 
deliberations,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse Jackson, whose endorsement the vice president also covets  
but has not yet secured, rallied workers with the sing-song cry, 
``Bush to the bushes,'' aimed at the Republicans' front-runner, 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, has spent months lobbying union officials to hold off  
and give him a chance to make his case. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the scenes, presidents of some of the AFL-CIO's biggest  
affiliated unions met twice Friday -- first, to hear from Sweeney 
that he wants ``very much'' to see the AFL-CIO endorse Gore before 
the biennial convention ends Wednesday, said union officials who 
spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second, smaller meeting, McEntee and other union presidents  
pushing hardest for an early nod to Gore -- including the American 
Federation of Teachers, the Firefighters and the Communications 
Workers -- assessed their potential vote count and who still needs 
persuasion, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney planned to meet separately with some wavering union  
boards on Sunday to press the case for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign chairman Tony Coelho and campaign manager Donna  
Brazile were headed to Los Angeles for last-minute lobbying, and 
the vice president set aside time to address the convention 
Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
