<HEADLINE> Daley Wants Stronger Jordan Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley  
called for stronger commercial and economic ties between American 
and Jordanian businesses at the start of his Middle East tour on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	During his two-day visit to Jordan, Daley was expected to  
discuss with his Jordanian counterpart Mohammed Asfour various ways 
of encouraging trade and investment between the two nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have come to Jordan and the Middle East to build on a  
valuable partnership between our public and private sectors that 
can contribute to -- and indeed accelerate -- economic growth, 
economic expansion and job creation,'' Daley said in a statement on 
arriving in Amman. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley also was to inaugurate a permanent U.S. Department of  
Commerce office in Amman to introduce visiting members of trade 
missions to key Jordanian officials. 
</P>
<P>
	A delegation of business executives was accompanying Daley to  
push their expertise in hopes of landing contracts in the region, 
Daley said before leaving the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	King Abdullah II, who was in Washington, met with Daley and the  
delegation before their departure to Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also was planning to visit Israel, the Palestinian  
territories, Egypt and Saudi Arabia. 
  	   	
