<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: US Needs Nuke Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A ban on testing of nuclear weapons is more  
important now than when President Eisenhower proposed it more than 
40 years ago, President Clinton said Saturday. He again urged the 
Senate to delay a treaty vote that means certain defeat for his 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	But a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said  
Tuesday's expected vote will go forward unless Clinton withdraws 
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty from consideration and promises 
not to submit it again. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty would impose a blanket international ban on all  
nuclear test explosions. The United States already is refraining 
from testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton sent the signed treaty to the Republican-led Senate two  
years ago, but conservatives had refused to hold debate on it 
before now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, only a week has been alloted to consider it,'' Clinton  
said in his weekly radio address, delivered in Chicago where 
Clinton traveled for a separate address to Hispanic leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is especially disturbing since the issue has been  
politicized ... a week is not enough time for an issue of this 
profound importance,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some congressional conservatives argue the United States should  
not give up its right to conduct nuclear tests. But Clinton and 
Democratic leaders say that substantive issue has taken a back seat 
to Republican zeal to score a partisan point. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, said: ``The  
White House has made a miscalculation to push for this treaty and 
this vote at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the treaty, also signed by 153 other countries, is  
America's best chance at nuclear security for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every year, the threat grows that nuclear weapons will  
spread,'' Clinton said. ``In the Middle East, the Persian Gulf and 
Asia, to areas where American troops are deployed,'' he said, ``to 
regions with intense rivalries, to rogue leaders and perhaps even 
to terrorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rejecting the pact would prevent the United States from taking  
the lead in halting the global spread of nuclear weapons, Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stakes are high.''  
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, the president acknowledged he lacks the votes in  
the Senate to ratify the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives have not backed off since their sudden move to  
schedule a vote for Tuesday. The Senate opened debate on the treaty 
on Friday, and Democrats have virtually no hope of rallying the 67 
votes needed to ratify it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
