<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France, Italy, Germany Make Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	World Cup champion France, Germany and Italy qualified for the  
European 2000 soccer championships Saturday, while England stayed 
in contention by squeezing into the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Also gaining automatic spots in next year's tournament were  
Yugoslavia, Romania and Portugal. Playoff berths were secured by 
Denmark, Ukraine, Turkey and Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of the day, the possibility existed that four of  
Europe's biggest soccer powers would fail to qualify for the 
16-team tournament in which the Netherlands and Belgium are 
co-hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	But France managed to win Group 4 by beating Iceland 3-2 and  
benefiting from a goalkeeping blunder that allowed Ukraine to gain 
a 1-1 tie with Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	With two minutes left in regulation, Russian goalkeeper  
Alexander Filimonov mishandled a simple cross and fell backward. 
The ball slipped from his hands into the net. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a personal catastrophe for me,'' Russian coach Oleg  
Romantsev said. ``We deserved a victory. A player of the quality 
like Filimonov's shouldn't miss such kicks and I will think twice 
before calling him to the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italy labored to a 0-0 tie against Belarus in Minsk, but the  
result was enough to clinch Group 1. Denmark, which had already 
completed its qualifying campaign, finished one point behind Italy 
in second place and will go into the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, the defending European champion, finished atop Group 3  
by playing to a 0-0 tie with Turkey in Munich. Turkey settled for a 
playoff spot. 
</P>
<P>
	In a battle between bitter Balkan rivals, Yugoslavia tied  
Croatia 2-2 in Zagreb to win Group 8. Ireland threw away a chance 
to win the group by giving up a 90th-minute goal in Macedonia and 
will go to the playoffs instead. Croatia, third-place finisher at 
the 1998 World Cup, finished third in the group and was eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Romania won Group 7 by beating Liechenstein 3-0, while Portugal  
downed Hungary 3-0 to claim an automatic qualifying spot as the 
best runner-up. The Portuguese finished with 23 points, three 
points ahead of the next best runner-up, Ukraine with 20 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czech Republic, which had already won Group 9, finished with  
a 10-0 record by beating the Faeroe Islands 2-0 in Prague. The 
Czechs, runners-up at the 1996 championships, are the first team 
European team ever to win all their qualifying games. 
</P>
<P>
	England got a reprieve when Sweden beat Poland 2-0 in Stockholm.  
The result ensured that England finished second in Group 5 and 
clinched a berth in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden already had qualified as a group winner and had nothing  
to play for Saturday. England needed a victory by Sweden, while 
Poland needed only a tie. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory left Sweden with 22 points. England and Poland both  
finished with 13 points, but England made the playoffs because of 
better head-to-head results. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway, Spain and the Czech Republic had qualified as group  
winners. Belgium and the Netherlands qualified automatically as 
co-hosts. Scotland and Slovenia had clinched playoff spots. 
</P>
<P>
	The eighth and final playoff spot will be filled by Israel or  
Cyprus, both in contention for the runner-up spot in Group 6. That 
will be determined Sunday when Israel plays at Spain and Cyprus at 
Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	The draw for the playoffs is Wednesday in Aachen, Germany. The  
first-leg games are Nov. 13-14 and the second leg Nov. 17. The four 
winners advance to the championships. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
