<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *John McLendon    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) -- Basketball Hall of Famer John  
McLendon, the last surviving student of Dr. James Naismith, the 
sport's creator, died Friday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	McLendon played at the University of Kansas in the early 1930s  
under Naismith. 
</P>
<P>
	In those days, blacks were barred from the university pool even  
though swimming was a graduation requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I jumped in and they drained the pool,'' McLendon recalled  
several years ago. ``Dr. Naismith wasn't about to have any of that 
so he sent over three of the biggest men on the basketball team to 
sit by the pool every time I swam. The administration wasn't happy, 
but there were no problems after that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLendon went on to a 25-year coaching career and was inducted  
into the Hall of Fame in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the first college coach to win three consecutive national  
titles, with Tennessee State of the NAIA from 1957 to 1959. The 
following season, he became the first black professional coach with 
the Cleveland Pipers of the American Basketball League. 

</P>
<P>
 *John C. Phillips    	
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- John C. Phillips, a retired Texas appeals  
court judge, died Saturday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, elected to the state Third Court of Appeals in 1963,  
was elected chief justice four years later and served in that 
capacity until his retirement in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	He served during World War II as an FBI special intelligence  
service agent in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips served as a Supreme Court briefing clerk, Texas  
Railroad Commission hearings examiner and assistant attorney 
general. 

</P>
<P>
 *John Skoglund    	
</P>
<P>
	ORONO, Minn. (AP) -- John Skoglund, the former Minnesota Vikings  
chairman, died Friday of lung cancer. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Skoglund was chairman of the Vikings' board until the team was  
sold last year. His father, insurance mogul H.P. Skoglund, was one 
of the original owners of the Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	As chairman, John Skoglund stayed out of the limelight. He said  
earlier this year that the satisfaction of owning part of the 
Vikings was enough for him. 

</P>
<P>
 *Jeremy Streck    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Former University of Kentucky football  
player Jeremy Streck, a starting senior guard last season, died 
Saturday of injuries suffered after being hit by a car. He was 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Streck had been in critical condition since he was struck on  
Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the accident, police charged a man with driving  
under the influence. There was no word on whether additional 
charges would be filed. 
</P>
<P>
	A 6-foot-5, 313-pound lineman from Cincinnati, Streck started 18  
games and played in 32 during his career at Kentucky. He started 
all 12 games last season at left guard as the Wildcats went 7-5, 
making their first appearance in a New Year's Day bowl game since 
1952. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
