<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Human Space Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China still hopes to put an astronaut in space,  
perhaps before the end of the year, Beijing's official newspapers 
reported Saturday, citing a senior executive in a government-run 
aerospace company. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang Liheng, deputy general manager of the China Aerospace  
Industrial Company, said plans for a launch of the manned 
spacecraft have been fixed for the century's end or early next 
century, the Beijing Daily and Beijing Evening News reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang provided no other details, as is usual in the vague  
official pronouncements on China's secretive space program. But the 
newspapers noted that extensive training has been given to a group 
of people who ``will become China's first generation of real 
astronauts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the program proves successful, China will become only the  
third country after the United States and the then-Soviet Union to 
achieve manned space flight. 
</P>
<P>
	China, an overwhelmingly rural country where farmers on average  
make $260 a year, sees its space program as a symbol of national 
strength. Many floats in the Oct. 1 National Day parade that marked 
50 years of communist rule carried models of rockets, including a 
Chinese version of the U.S. space shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese aerospace officials announced earlier this year that  
they hoped to launch the manned spacecraft around the anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	Western experts who track the Chinese space program believe that  
China has a new rocket to carry a reusable manned craft into orbit, 
but no shuttle-type vehicle. In the experts' opinion, China will 
have to conduct one, if not two, unmanned test launches of the 
craft before sending it up with astronauts inside. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the experts say, there have been no signs that a test  
has been conducted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
