<DOCNO> APW19991009.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 08:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush's Slogan Has Family Roots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is taking pains in  
politics to be his own man, but a new biography says the Republican 
presidential candidate is using a slogan that was applied to his 
father. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compassionate conservative'' was used by Ron Kaufman, an aide  
to the senior Bush when he was running for president in the 
mid-1980s, in a Christian magazine article designed to make 
religious conservatives comfortable with the candidate, the 
biography says. 
</P>
<P>
	``First Son: George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty,'' was  
released Sunday. The book, the first in a new series of competing 
biographies coming out on the GOP front-runner, was written by Bill 
Minutaglio, a Dallas Morning News reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	The evenhanded book leaves unsettled two questions from the  
governor's past. It avoids any ``dollops of drug tales'' -- the 
long-standing, still-unsubstantiated speculation about whether the 
younger Bush ever used illegal drugs; and it offers no proof his 
family pulled strings to keep him out of the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	``First Son'' details Bush's time living in Washington when he  
served as ``loyalty monitor'' in his father's presidential 
campaign. He was also the family's liaison with ascendant leaders 
of the religious right, who worried the vice president was not 
nearly as in tune with their issues as President Reagan was. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1986, the month the younger Bush suddenly stopped his  
years of hard drinking, the evangelical magazine Christian Herald 
published a cover story written by a Bush campaign aide in which 
Kaufman, head of the vice president's political action committee, 
said the candidate was best described as a ``compassionate 
conservative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The phrase gained limited currency in the 1988 campaign. It was  
used to describe both the vice president and a rival for the GOP 
nomination that year, Bob Dole. Indeed, Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch 
of Utah, now running against the younger Bush, called himself a 
compassionate conservative way back in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the slogan is at the core of the governor's campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	The book says that once the vice president won the election, his  
son helped hand out political favors. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Minutaglio writes, the younger Bush suggested a  
wealthy Texas publisher, Roger Horchow, be appointed chairman of 
the National Endowment for the Arts because he had given money to 
the Bush campaign. But when aides discovered the publisher had also 
contributed to Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis, he scratched 
his name from the list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 20:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 6 Tenn. 37, No. 10 Georgia 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tee Martin ran for three touchdowns and  
threw for another Saturday to lead No. 6 Tennessee to a 37-20 
victory over No. 10 Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Volunteers (4-1, 2-1 Southeastern Conference) also got a  
100-yard kickoff return from Leonard Scott to became the first team 
ever to beat Georgia (4-1, 2-1) in nine straight meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vols' victory also forged a three-way tie at the top of the  
SEC Eastern Division among Tennessee, Georgia and Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving with an injured right (throwing) wrist in the  
fourth quarter, Martin led the Vols to 458 total yards. He 
completed 21 of 35 passes for 283 yards, with a touchdown and two 
interceptions. The extent of Martin's injury was not immediately 
known. 
</P>
<P>
	Cedrick Wilson led the Tennessee receivers with eight catches  
for 107 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs had been averaging 191 yards a game on the ground  
this year, but Tennessee held them to 54 yards on 30 carries. 
Jasper Sanks, who had gone over 100 yards three straight games, had 
37 yards on eight carries. 
</P>
<P>
	Quincy Carter completed 20 of 34 passes for 228 yards and two  
touchdowns despite heavy pressure most of the night. Terrence 
Edwards had five catches for 98 yards and a score. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee took control with a 21-point second quarter for a 28-7  
lead at the break, then added the only points of the third quarter 
on a safety when Georgia punter Wynn Kopp fell on a high center 
snap at his own goal line to make it 30-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia made it interesting for a time early in the fourth  
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter led the 'Dogs on a 71-yard drive to score on his 4-yard  
pass to Jevaris Johnson with 14:16 left to play. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tennessee's next series, Jamie Henderson intercepted a Martin  
pass and returned it 49 yards for a touchdown to narrow the Vols' 
lead to 30-20 with 12 1/2 minutes still to play. 
</P>
<P>
	But Scott took the ensuing kickoff 100 yards to extend the  
margin back to 37-20, much to the relief of most of the crowd of 
107,247 who endured a steady, light rain the entire game. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was still erratic throwing the ball early, as he has been  
since injuring his throwing shoulder against Florida, but several 
times bailed the Vols out of trouble with timely scrambles. 
</P>
<P>
	His three scoring runs all came in the first half and covered 3,  
6 and 1 yard. He also scrambled for 22 yards on a third-and-15, and 
20 yards to the Georgia 9 to set up a 10-yard touchdown pass to 
Jamal Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin's third TD run came with 24 seconds left in the half to  
cap an 82-yard drive in 10 plays to beat the clock and give the 
Volunteers a 28-7 lead at the break. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee scored with its opening drive, going 63 yards in nine  
plays. The biggest was a 34-yard completion to Eric Parker. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia drove 90 yards in 12 plays to tie it 7-7 late in the  
first quarter. Carter converted two long third downs. The touchdown 
came on a 27-yard pass from Carter to Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee went 82 yards with the ensuing possession to score on  
the screen pass to Lewis for a 14-7 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	After Georgia went three-and-out, the Vols drove 65 yards in  
seven plays to go ahead 21-7. Martin scored on a 6-yard sweep 
around right end. 
</P>
<P>
	The drive to beat the halftime clock was salvaged early on.  
Cedrick Wilson recovered his own fumble when two Georgia players 
had a good shot at it on the second play at the Tennessee 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin completed passes of 16 yards to Eric Parker, 19 to Lewis,  
17 to David Martin and 9 to Parker to march the Vols to the Georgia 
13 with the clock winding down and Tennessee out of timeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis got 11 yards on first down, then took it to the 1 on the  
next play. Martin sneaked in with 24 seconds left in the half. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
