<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 08:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Air Force Shells Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- The Russian air force attacked  
suspected rebel bases and training centers in Chechnya, and seven 
Russian soldiers were killed in ground clashes, news reports said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian artillery shelled targets in Chechnya as federal troops  
continued to fortify their positions in the northern third of the 
breakaway republic, the Interfax news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven Russian soldiers were killed and 37 were wounded in the  
latest fighting to establish a security zone in Chechnya, a Defense 
Ministry spokesman said, according to Interfax. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry's press service said 50 Islamic militants were  
killed in the clashes, which wiped out a rebel base near the 
village of Naurskaya, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Russian outpost on the border between Chechnya and Dagestan  
came under automatic weapons fire during the night from separatist 
bases inside Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. There 
were no reports of casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian ground forces invaded Chechnya two weeks ago. They want  
to establish a security zone there to prevent Muslim separatists 
from attacking neighboring regions in southern Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States had accused Russia on Friday of violating the  
Conventional Forces in Europe agreement, which limits the number of 
tanks, artillery pieces, aircraft and other non-nuclear arms in 
Europe and sets specific ceilings for particular regions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said today that Russia  
had notified the West about its military deployment in the Caucasus 
region and that a temporary buildup was within the treaty's 
framework. 
</P>
<P>
	``The possibility of a temporary deployment of forces is  
provided for,'' Ivanov said. ``Here we are not committing any 
violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington says Moscow cannot claim its deployment is temporary,  
since it has long violated higher weapon ceilings for southern 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Militants twice invaded Dagestan this summer, and are blamed by  
Moscow for a series of September apartment explosions in Russia 
that killed about 300 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, refugees continued to flood from Chechnya into  
neighboring Ingushetia. About 142,000 people have fled the region 
so far, Interfax reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingush President Ruslan Aushev told Interfax that food, tents  
and other vital supplies to take care of the refugees were in short 
supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``This situation is a humanitarian catastrophe for us,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 22:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Advances in World Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIANJIN, China (AP) -- The United States needed Vanessa Atler's  
final 9.762 in floor exercises Sunday to advance to the medal round 
of the World Gymnastics Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Andreea Raducan and Maria Olaru had led defending champion  
Romania to the best qualifying score Saturday, which held up while 
the final nine of the 40 women's teams competed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team, entirely new since the 1996 Olympic team won the  
gold medal, was in danger of finishing just out of the top six -- 
missing a spot in the medal round -- before Atler came through with 
her best score of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States safely made the top 12 that qualify for next  
year's Olympics in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	Romania topped qualifying with 154.394 points, Russia had  
153.576 and Ukraine 151.970. 
</P>
<P>
	Competing Sunday, 1997 bronze medalist China moved into fourth  
place with 151.720 and the Americans scored 151.001. Australia also 
made the final round with 150.688. 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the Olympic qualifiers, Spain had 150.407, France  
149.451, Italy 148.545, Canada 148.533, Britain 146.982 and Belarus 
145.856. Japan just missed qualifying with 145.740. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-year-old Raducan scored 9.812 on the balance beam and  
9.800 in the floor exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	Olaru's best score was a 9.787 on the floor, but her consistency  
put her into the individual lead with 38.792 to 38.755 for Raducan. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Svetlana Khorkina, the defending individual champion,  
stood third in the competition for 36 places in the individual 
all-around medal round with 38.699. She had the best individual 
mark of 9.837, on the uneven bars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans ran into problems on the uneven bars, but this  
time Atler came through with a clean program after falls from the 
bars cost her national championships this year and last. She scored 
9.475. 
</P>
<P>
	American champion Kristen Maloney fell the wrong way out of a  
handstand and scored just 8.975. Elise Ray added vital points with 
a 9.600. 
</P>
<P>
	But Maloney and Atler both scored 9.612 on the balance beam, and  
Maloney had 9.750 on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Atler stood seventh among individuals with 38.367.  
</P>
<P>
	Men's qualifying was to start later Sunday. China, seeking its  
fourth consecutive world title, was to compete Sunday night, with 
Russia and the United States scheduled Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
