<DOCNO> APW19991009.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 17:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Convicted in Jail Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GALVESTON, Texas (AP) -- A former jailer was convicted Saturday  
on a misdemeanor count of violating a Missouri inmate's rights by 
kicking him after he had complied with orders to lie down during a 
videotaped 1996 jail shakedown. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the jury found Wilton David Wallace and another  
officer, Robert Percival, innocent on felony counts that would have 
meant up to 10 years in prison and a fine of up to $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace faces probation or up to a year in jail on the lesser  
count, which did not allege bodily injury. Percival was acquitted 
on both counts and left the courtroom crying. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury said it was unable to reach a verdict on a canine  
officer, David Cisneros, whose dog bit the prisoner, convicted 
murderer Toby Hawthorne. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they are uncertain whether they'll try Cisneros  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Lt. Lester Arnold, who used a stun gun on the inmates at  
the Brazoria County Jail, pleaded guilty to this reduced charge 
last week to avoid trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was tried before U.S. District Judge Kenneth Hoyt.  
</P>
<P>
	It's the second civil rights violation for Wallace, who served  
five months in federal prison for a 1983 offense against a 
prisoner. His attorney said he will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing the video, ostensibly made for training purposes,  
the state of Missouri canceled its private jail contract and moved 
its prisoners out of the state. The tape showed prisoners being 
electrically jolted and kicked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
