<DOCNO> APW19991009.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 12:42:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Seeks Different Energy Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HACHIJO ISLAND, Japan (AP) -- Cows doze underneath a row of shiny  
white windmills. Tucked away in a nearby jungle, flowers grow in 
greenhouses heated by a volcano's geothermal energy. 
</P>
<P>
	The look of Japan's energy future?  
</P>
<P>
	Hardly, experts say. Although there are a few pockets of  
experimental projects, like this remote island southeast of Tokyo, 
nuclear energy will likely remain a major part of any solution to 
resource-poor Japan's power problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Nuclear power accounts for roughly 35 percent of Japan's energy.  
That is behind France, which has about a 78 percent reliance on 
nuclear power, but well ahead of the United States' 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next 10 years, Japan's government plans to boost the  
nuclear share to more than 40 percent by bringing new reactors 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	To further reduce dependence on imported oil, Japan also has  
been developing reactors fueled by plutonium, a highly radioactive 
element that can be used to make nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	For those hoping to find ways to pull Japan away from its  
decades-old commitment to nuclear energy, Hachijo Island is 
something of a cause celebre. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials initiated an ``Eco Island'' program here several years  
ago, hoping to turn the island's incessant winds and twin volcanoes 
into natural generators of clean, safe energy. 
</P>
<P>
	But even on an island with only 9,000 residents, that aim is  
proving a difficult task, officials say. And as a model for the 
rest of Japan, this island's message is bleak. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, our geothermal plant can supply the needs for about  
30 percent of the island at night, when use is at its lowest,'' 
said Ryo Kikuchi, a planner at the island's town hall. ``I doubt if 
we will ever really increase that share very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power companies say the reason is cost.  
</P>
<P>
	Generating electricity from wind, for example, costs from two to  
three times as much as producing it with nuclear reactors, the 
Agency of Natural Resources and Energy says. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of nuclear power say safety, not cost, should be the  
primary issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to make a political decision to convert from nuclear  
to natural energy,'' said Sanae Shida of Greenpeace Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	There is relatively little pressure on the government to make  
such a decision, however. Japan has never had a very powerful 
environmental movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The share of energy generated by alternative sources is  
virtually zero,'' said Yoshimi Hitosugi of Tokyo Electric Co. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 10:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
