<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NetAid Concerts Aim To Help Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The United Nations is hoping to tap into a new  
generation of philanthropists and bring attention to world poverty 
on Saturday with overlapping rock concerts in three cities -- all 
broadcast live on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	One billion hits are expected on the U.N. Development Program's  
Web site, where Internet surfers can log on and rock on with, among 
others, David Bowie and the Eurythmics in London, Bryan Ferry in 
Geneva, and Bono, Sting and Puff Daddy at Giants Stadium in East 
Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Local television and radio stations also will carry the concerts  
live. 
</P>
<P>
	Official development aid has dwindled in recent years, and the  
U.N. agency is hoping to convince a new generation to open their 
minds and wallets to alleviate world poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it won't let governments off the hook,'' spokesman Mark  
Malloch Brown said Friday in London. ``I think this will build 
pressure on them when they see this message going out to a wider 
group of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers will be asked to donate money by entering their credit  
card information on the Web site or pledging a future donation. 
</P>
<P>
	With a click of a mouse, money can be directed to one of five  
designated areas: ending hunger, helping refugees, saving the 
environment, securing human rights or relieving debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of thousands of dollars have poured into the site, the  
United Nations said. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time in the history of mankind, we have the  
capacity to tackle poverty,'' said U.N. spokesman Jean Fabre, 
speaking to reporters in Geneva. ``NetAid is mobilizing artists and 
the Internet so that people have the possibility to be informed and 
also to be linked up together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- The U.N. Development Program's Web site address  
is www.netaid.org 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
