<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Greenwood Lake Wins at Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Greenwood Lake likes to do it his way -- and that  
way is unnerving for a trainer and owner. 
</P>
<P>
	It also was the winning way Saturday as the colt came from way  
out of it to win the 1 1-16-mile Champagne for 2-year-olds at 
Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why he takes himself back, but that's the way he  
likes to run,'' trainer Nick Zito said after his second straight 
victory in the Champagne. He won with The Groom Is Red last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just know he's not going to make it; he's too far back,''  
co-owner Joseph Cornacchia said of Greenwood Lake, who was last in 
the seven-horse field for the first three-quarters of a mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Jean-Luc Samyn, Greenwood Lake was 9 lengths behind  
with a little more than a quarter-mile remaining, but he was 2 1/2 
lengths ahead at the wire after charging past Chief Seattle with 
about 30 yards remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	In the race following the Champagne, Val's Prince took the lead  
just inside the eighth pole and won the 1 1/2-mile Turf Classic by a 
length over Dream Well for his second straight victory in a Grade I 
stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	While Greenwood Lake raced into the 2-year-old championship  
picture, favored More Than Ready finished a dismal fifth for his 
second straight loss after five straight victories that had made 
him the division leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwood Lake, winning for the second time in four starts,  
carried home scale weight of 122 pounds in 1:43 3-5 and paid 
$15.60, $5.10 and $3.20. He earned $240,000 from a $400,000 purse 
for owners Cornacchia, Dolores Conway and Fred Dematteis. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Seattle paid $3.90 and $3, and High Yield returned $2.60  
for show. 
</P>
<P>
	Val's Prince, who won the Man o'War in his previous start,  
marked himself as the serious contender for the $2 million 
Breeders' Cup Turf on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park. Yagli, the 8-5 
favorite, was trapped on the hedge in the stretch and wasn't a 
factor in his second straight defeat after having won three 
straight stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Val's Prince, a 7-year-old gelding owned by Weiner Martin,  
carried home 126 in 2:28 3-5 and earned $360,000 from a purse of 
$600,000. He paid $8.10, $3.80 and $3. He is trained by James Bond, 
trainer of Behrens, the favorite for the $1 million Jockey Club 
Gold Cup Sunday at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought Val's Prince was the best turf horse in the  
country, Bond said, ``He sure looks that way to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	France-based Dream Well, making his U.S. debut, returned $4.10  
and $3.60 after finishing neck in front of Fahris in the 
seven-horse field. Fahris paid $5.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
