<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 10:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Seeks Compromise on Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a year marked by brinkmanship over tax  
cuts and the budget surplus, congressional Republicans are trying 
to avoid a new confrontation with the White House on a must-pass 
bill renewing expiring tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	At a closed-door meeting last week, Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott said a 10-year, $75 billion proposal from the chairman of the 
Senate Finance Committee, Republican William Roth of Delaware, was 
too costly to pass, according to a participant's notes of the 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., urged a more modest alternative that would renew  
the tax breaks for another two years, long enough to get past the 
2000 election. If a Republican wins the White House, Lott's 
reasoning went, Congress would have a fresh opportunity to pass 
much broader tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Lott said his message to the Finance Committee was to  
come up with a noncontroversial ``clean'' bill. ``It's got to be as 
low as possible in terms of cost,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	This move toward moderation on the tax ``extenders'' bill stands  
in stark contrast to the GOP's position earlier this year on the 
10-year, $792 billion tax cut. Republicans defied President 
Clinton's veto threat on that bill and then touted it as 
confirmation of the vast philosophical gulf between the GOP and 
Democrats on tax cuts vs. higher spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Disagreement remains over whether to use any of the projected  
budget surplus on this smaller tax bill -- most of which was part of 
the bigger tax cut -- or find revenue offsets to pay for it. The 
difference in this debate is that both sides stand to lose 
politically if the bill fails. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel an urgency to pass the extenders,'' said Senate  
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost every year, Congress must decide whether to renew -- or  
extend -- a batch of business tax breaks. Foremost among them is a 
credit for research and development popular with the high-tech 
industry and manufacturers; the credit expired June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers and lobbyists say this exercise is set up  
deliberately by Congress so there is a must-pass tax bill every 
year, ensuring a vehicle that can carry other pet items. But Rep. 
Bill Archer, chairman of the tax-writing House Ways and Means 
Committee, said a periodic review of such credits is a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``You ought to be able to reassess the program and see how it's  
working,'' said Archer, R-Texas, who included a five-year extension 
of the research credit in his version of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Not passing an extenders bill this year runs the risk of  
alienating the high-tech business sector being courted so actively 
by Democrats and Republicans. There also are important 
constituencies for expiring credits for businesses that hire former 
welfare recipients and people who traditionally have difficulty 
holding jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Even worse, an estimated 1 million average taxpayers unwittingly  
could fall subject to the intricate alternative minimum tax because 
they claim personal credits such as the $500 per-child credit or 
education credits. The AMT was created to prevent the wealthy from 
escaping income taxes through legal means, but with inflation it is 
gradually creeping up on middle-class taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is now coming up and rear-ending people,'' said Rep. Nancy  
Johnson, R-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless those personal credits are excluded from AMT, taxpayers  
working on their returns in early 2000 -- right during primary 
election season -- could be in for a costly surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe this Congress will fail to extend these  
expiring provisions,'' Archer said. ``There are too many important 
things in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite bipartisan sentiment to fix the AMT problem and extend  
the business credits, how the measure is paid for stands in the 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and the Democrats repeatedly have opposed any tax relief  
that spends projected budget surpluses unless steps are taken 
toward the long-term solvency of Social Security and Medicare, 
including a new prescription drug benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should do something,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of  
New York, top Democrat on the Finance Committee. ``What we do must 
be paid for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats are suggesting a number of revenue offsets for a  
two-year extenders bill, including a proposal to close a number of 
corporate tax shelters and a reinstatement of a Superfund 
environmental cleanup tax. But Democrats also are hinting that some 
surplus money could be available for extenders in future years 
under certain conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no opposition, no difficulty with the concept of using  
non-Social Security revenues in the future so long as we recognize 
there's a very narrow amount of money,'' Daschle said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Lott spokesman John Czwartacki said  
Republicans are examining ways to pay for the extenders without 
spending surplus dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a sense that we would like an offset,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Roth and Moynihan have been discussing a compromise measure that  
could come before the Finance Committee as early as Wednesday. 
Pending before the House, meanwhile, is a five-year, $23.3 billion 
version that extends the research credit for five years and makes 
permanent the AMT fix mostly with projected surplus money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
