<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quaker Oats To Pay 3.2M Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Quaker Oats Co. has agreed to pay $3.2 million to  
settle age discrimination claims filed on behalf of sales staffers 
who lost their jobs in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission filed the  
claims after finding ``reasonable cause'' to believe the 
Chicago-based company violated the Age Discrimination in Employment 
Act of 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement was announced Friday. In it, the company admitted  
no wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quaker Oats firmly believes it did not discriminate against  
older employees during its 1994 sales force restructuring,'' said 
Robert S. Morrison, the company's chairman, president and chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Three hundred jobs were cut during the restructuring.  
</P>
<P>
	Several private lawsuits have been filed by people who lost jobs  
in 1994, Morrison said. But he said there has been no court ruling 
that the company discriminated against older employees. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
