<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 4 Nebraska 42, Iowa St. 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Eric Crouch threw for two touchdowns and  
ran for another as No. 4 Nebraska routed Iowa State 49-14 Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Correll Buckhalter and Dan Alexander each topped 100 yards  
rushing and Derrahn Diedrick ran for 99 for the Cornhuskers (6-0, 
3-0 Big 12), who haven't lost to Iowa State in Lincoln since 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska gained 524 yards against a defense that had been  
allowing only 215 per game and held the Cyclones (3-2, 0-2), who 
were leading the nation in rushing with 328 yards per game, to 185. 
The Huskers shut down Iowa State tailback Darren Davis, the 
nation's leading rusher, until the fourth quarter, when he was able 
to get free long after Nebraska coach Frank Solich had pulled his 
starters. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who was averaging 176.8 yards, finished with 107 on 22  
carries and scored two touchdowns, both in the fourth quarter. 
Davis had just 40 yards on 15 carries heading into the final 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cyclones, who have been outscored 199-42 in their last three  
visits to Lincoln, were penalized 12 times for 99 yards, including 
one for roughing the punter that kept a Nebraska scoring drive 
alive. They also had two punts blocked, fumbled twice and threw one 
interception. 
</P>
<P>
	Crouch, who left midway through the third quarter, was 5-for-10  
passing for 85 yards, with touchdown throws of 47 yards to Matt 
Davison and 24 yards to Bobby Newcombe. He also ran for 58 yards on 
10 carries, including a 20-yard dash early in the third quarter 
that put Nebraska up 42-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander finished with 135 yards on 10 carries, the first time  
he broke 100 yards in a game this season. Buckhalter, who topped 
100 against Missouri two weeks ago, carried 14 times for 127. 
Buckhalter's 7-yard touchdown run gave the Huskers a 28-0 halftime 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska defensive back Joe Walker, who missed the first few  
games while recovering from knee surgery, forced two fumbles that 
resulted in Cornhusker touchdowns. Walker sacked Sage Rosenfels 
from the blind side early in the first quarter and recovered the 
fumble, setting up the Huskers' 62-yard drive that ended on 
Alexander's 7-yard run to give Nebraska a 7-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Early in the fourth quarter, Walker sacked Derrick Walker and  
reserve end Demoine Adams scooped up the ball and returned it 37 
yards for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska cornerback Ralph Brown scored on a blocked punt he  
recovered in the end zone, putting Nebraska up 14-0 with 5:44 left 
in the first quarter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
