<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Slave Labor Offer Said Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- A spokesman for German industry said Saturday he  
is confident negotiators will agree on compensation for Nazi-era 
slave laborers, even though representatives of survivors have 
criticized a German offer of $3.3 billion as too low. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Wolfgang Gibowski urged attorneys and survivor groups  
to accept the proposal, saying German companies are not prepared to 
pay more. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our best and final offer,'' he said in a telephone  
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan proposed Thursday by German negotiators in  
Washington, industry would finance two-thirds and the government 
one-third of a fund for former slave laborers and other ``forgotten 
victims'' who have received little or no restitution for Nazi 
evils. 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder on Friday defended the German offer  
as ``worthy.'' The offer was spurred by U.S. class-action lawsuits 
against German companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The next round of negotiations is scheduled for Nov. 16-17 in  
Bonn, Germany. Gibowski did not rule out a collapse of the talks, 
but he said he was optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect the attorneys and survivor groups to be ready to work  
on a solution of the problem and to talk about the money that's on 
the table,'' Gibowski told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	If no overall settlement can be found, individual companies  
could set up their own funds to compensate slave laborers who 
worked for them during World War II, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mass-circulation Bild am Sonntag newspaper quoted Gibowski  
as saying it was ``not fair'' that German companies ``are being 
insulted'' by critics of the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	A Jewish leader said he also expects a settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	Israel Singer, general secretary of the World Jewish Congress,  
said on German radio late Friday that he has ``great trust'' German 
negotiators will find a solution. It was unclear whether he found 
the German offer acceptable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
