<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Rail Unions Criticize London Co.  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Rail unions expressed disgust when they learned  
that some of the train cars involved in Tuesday's deadly crash had 
been salvaged from another crash two years ago. Deputy Prime 
Minister John Prescott announced an investigation into rail safety 
under Railtrack, the company that owns and operates Britain's 
formerly nationalized rail service. At least 40 people perished 
Tuesday when two passenger trains collided two miles west of 
London's Paddington Station, Scotland Yard said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore, Bradley Tangle Over Party Loyalty  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley tangled over  
their political loyalties today in a rare showdown of Democratic 
presidential candidates, with the vice president suggesting his 
rival abandoned the party in its darkest hours. ``I did not walk 
away,'' Gore said. Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, suggested 
Gore resorted to attacks because he lacked vision. ``To the extent 
that someone is confident in their own vision of the future, they 
don't need to resort to the darts,'' Bradley said. ``I think I can 
talk about the future in a way that's compelling enough.'' 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Rivals Criticize Bush  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Conservative candidates vying for the  
Republican presidential nomination criticized front-runner George 
W. Bush today for ``beating up on the conservatives'' and 
distancing himself from core GOP values. At the National Federation 
of Republican Assemblies convention, each candidate mentioned the 
Texas governor directly, criticizing Bush's stance on big 
government and his reluctance to require that all judge appointees 
oppose abortion rights. 

</P>
<P>
	16 Die As Bus Overturns in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A bus carrying members of a singles club  
overturned on a slippery northern Israel road Saturday and plunged 
into a deep ravine, killing 16 people, police said. Thirty-six 
people were injured, 10 of them seriously, in what police called 
Israel's deadliest road accident. The bus was taking 56 members of 
a singles club from central Israel on an outing when the first 
heavy rain in months began falling, leaving the road slick. 

</P>
<P>
	Austria Assures Israel on Haider  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima told  
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak that his leading Socialist 
Democrats would not enter a coalition with Joerg Haider and his 
anti-immigrant Freedom Party because Haider's comments are 
``unacceptable,'' Klima's spokesman told the Austria Press Agency. 
Haider's electoral success has alarmed Israel because of his 
comments years ago in praise of Adolf Hitler's ``decent employment 
policies.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Immigrant Ship Sinks Near Guatemala  
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A boat filled with illegal Chinese  
immigrants sank today off the Guatemalan coast. Five were killed 
and 38 were rescued, authorities said. The shipwreck occurred in 
the Pacific Ocean off Chiquimulia, 70 miles south of Guatemala 
City. The boat sank during bad weather, Guatemalan immigration 
spokeswoman Sonia Ortiz said. It was unclear where the boat was 
coming from, but Ortiz said it was believed the immigrants were 
headed to Mexico and planned to continue by land from there to the 
United States. Ortiz said the survivors would be deported. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford, UAW Reach Tentative Deal  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- The United Auto Workers and Ford Motor  
Co. reached a tentative agreement today on a new contract for 
100,000 workers. A joint statement announcing the deal contained no 
details, but a source close to the talks said the agreement 
followed the pattern set by the UAW in deals with General Motors 
Corp. and DaimlerChrysler AG -- four-year agreements with raises of 
3 percent each year and a signing bonus. 

</P>
<P>
	Miami Gives Cuban Band Cold Shoulder  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A performance by one of Cuba's hottest bands drew  
about 2,000 anti-Castro protesters to Miami Arena tonight, with 
many waving flags, shouting slogans and denouncing the show. After 
being warmly welcomed elsewhere during a tour of the United States, 
Los Van Van got the cold shoulder in the heart of the Cuban exile 
community. Demonstrators carried signs reading ``Castro: 40 years 
of dictatorship and 40 years of slavery'' and ``Van: Get out of 
Miami.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Stay Alive; Mets, Braves Advance  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The New York Mets and the Atlanta Braves advanced  
to the National League Championship Series today while the Boston 
Red Sox avoided first-round sweep in the American League playoffs. 
The Mets' Todd Pratt homered in the 10th inning for a 4-3 win over 
Arizona as New York took the series three games to one. In Houston, 
the Braves clinched its opening-round series with a 7-5 victory 
over the Astros. In Boston, the Red Sox beat the Cleveland Indians 
9-3 behind a strong pitching performance from Ramon Martinez. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  













  	   	
</P>
