<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson's Season Ends Inside Dugout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Randy Johnson could only watch from the dugout  
as the Arizona Diamondbacks' season came to an end. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter's decision to save his biggest gun for a  
fifth game backfired as the Diamondbacks lost Game 4 to the New 
York Mets 4-3 in 10 innings and were eliminated in a game Brian 
Anderson started. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how Randy could have pitched any better than Brian  
Anderson did,'' Showalter said of Anderson, who allowed two runs in 
seven innings. ``We felt it was our best option and we are 
comfortable with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson ended this season the way the AL's most dominating  
starter went out last season. Boston's Pedro Martinez also watched 
Game 4 against Cleveland in 1998, as Pete Schourek started and the 
Red Sox were eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course I wanted to pitch,'' Johnson said. ``But I had my  
turn, and I had to wait for my next one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, Arizona's $52.4 million ace, was 5-2 with a 2.55 ERA on  
three days' rest over the last six seasons. One of those wins came 
in the first round of the 1995 playoffs, when Johnson beat 
Showalter and the Yankees in the third game, leading Seattle into 
the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	But he hadn't pitched on three days' rest since 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know everyone is kind of reaching back for 1995,'' Showalter  
said. ``Randy is older and ... who we have pitching today compared 
to who they had at that point back then, there is a lot of 
differences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing into Showalter's decision is what happened to Johnson  
after the Mariners overused him down the stretch in 1995. Johnson 
missed nearly all of 1996 with a back injury and the Diamondbacks 
weren't willing to risk their biggest investment to win a 
first-round series. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole idea here is not just to get through one round, but  
to be able to get through all of them,'' Showalter said. ``It is a 
real juggling act because you want to stay as strong as possible 
because what does it mean to win this series if you can't win the 
next one too?'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the core of this team expected to stay intact, Johnson said  
it won't be too long until that next postseason begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the talent we have on this team, no question we will be  
back,'' he said. ``It's not going out on a limb with the players, 
the leadership, the coaches and the ownership we have, that we'll 
be back in the playoffs again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that pitching Johnson would have guaranteed anything. He had  
lost his last six postseason decisions -- a major league record -- 
and was shelled for seven runs in eight-plus innings in a 138-pitch 
outing in Game 1 Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, the Mets sure weren't eager to face him again.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were looking over our shoulder at Randy Johnson,'' Mets  
manager Bobby Valentine said. ``If they say they weren't, I don't 
think they would be telling the truth.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
