<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Air Force Shells Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- The Russian air force attacked  
suspected rebel bases and training centers in Chechnya, and seven 
Russian soldiers were killed in ground clashes, news reports said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian artillery shelled targets in Chechnya as federal troops  
continued to fortify their positions in the northern third of the 
breakaway republic, the Interfax news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven Russian soldiers were killed and 37 were wounded in the  
latest fighting to establish a security zone in Chechnya, a Defense 
Ministry spokesman said, according to Interfax. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry's press service said 50 Islamic militants were  
killed in the clashes, which wiped out a rebel base near the 
village of Naurskaya, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Russian outpost on the border between Chechnya and Dagestan  
came under automatic weapons fire during the night from separatist 
bases inside Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. There 
were no reports of casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian ground forces invaded Chechnya two weeks ago. They want  
to establish a security zone there to prevent Muslim separatists 
from attacking neighboring regions in southern Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States had accused Russia on Friday of violating the  
Conventional Forces in Europe agreement, which limits the number of 
tanks, artillery pieces, aircraft and other non-nuclear arms in 
Europe and sets specific ceilings for particular regions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said today that Russia  
had notified the West about its military deployment in the Caucasus 
region and that a temporary buildup was within the treaty's 
framework. 
</P>
<P>
	``The possibility of a temporary deployment of forces is  
provided for,'' Ivanov said. ``Here we are not committing any 
violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington says Moscow cannot claim its deployment is temporary,  
since it has long violated higher weapon ceilings for southern 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Militants twice invaded Dagestan this summer, and are blamed by  
Moscow for a series of September apartment explosions in Russia 
that killed about 300 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, refugees continued to flood from Chechnya into  
neighboring Ingushetia. About 142,000 people have fled the region 
so far, Interfax reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingush President Ruslan Aushev told Interfax that food, tents  
and other vital supplies to take care of the refugees were in short 
supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``This situation is a humanitarian catastrophe for us,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
