<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India Aviation Finishes Y2K Upgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's civil aviation industry has  
upgraded its equipment and trained pilots and engineers to make 
sure computers don't go haywire on New Year's Day, an official said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are Y2K compliant. We have taken all precautions. We're not  
taking chances on anything,'' said P.V. Jayakrishnan, the top 
bureaucrat at the Civil Aviation Ministry, which controls all 
aviation activity in India. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 1,200 aircraft operate in Indian airspace every day, half  
of them landing or taking off from its airports, with a total of 
70,000 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Y2K fears stem from computers that use only two digits to  
represent the year, meaning they could read 2000 as 1900 and 
malfunction. 
</P>
<P>
	Early last year, the government ordered its civilian and  
military airports to implement the changes required under 
international air safety rules, Jayakrishnan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without the changes, the economics of international air travel  
can go awry if India is not Y2K compliant, especially since India 
is strategically located for civil aviation purposes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said all the systems have been tested and found  
satisfactory in tests conducted both by Indian and foreign 
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
