<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Nuclear Test Ban  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton said today a ban on nuclear  
testing is more important now than when President Eisenhower 
proposed it more than 40 years ago. He again urged the Senate to 
delay a treaty vote that means certain defeat for his 
administration. The Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty would impose a 
blanket international ban on all nuclear test explosions. Clinton 
said the treaty, also signed by 153 other countries, is America's 
best chance at nuclear security for the future. ``Every year, the 
threat grows that nuclear weapons will spread,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Captures Chechnya Town  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops backed by tanks and  
artillery captured a strategic town in Chechnya Saturday after 
heavy fighting, while Moscow denied that it was breaking an 
international arms treaty by boosting its forces in the breakaway 
republic. Russian troops seized a town in the west of the mountain 
republic, but were repelled by Chechen fighters when they tried to 
advance, Chechen commander Hamzat Gilayev told The Associated 
Press. Moscow has said it wants to establish a security zone to 
prevent Islamic militants from attacking regions in southern 
Russia. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Readies Ads for Forbes Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	FORT DODGE, Iowa (AP) -- Bracing for a rival's onslaught, George  
W. Bush's political team has produced and tested a huge package of 
potential campaign advertisements -- including several designed to 
look like attack ads he could face. In focus groups conducted by 
the Bush team, the simulated attacks from wealthy publisher Steve 
Forbes did not hurt the Texas governor's standing when coupled with 
a Bush ad responding to the criticism, said knowledgeable officials 
close to the Bush campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore, Bradley Sharpen Differences  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley tangled over  
their party loyalties today in a rare showdown of Democratic 
presidential candidates, with the vice president suggesting his 
rival abandoned the party in its darkest hours. ``I did not walk 
away,'' the vice president said as the pair prepared for late-night 
addresses before Democratic activists. Bradley, a former New Jersey 
senator, suggested Gore resorted to attacks because he lacked 
vision. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford, UAW Reach Tentative Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- The United Auto Workers and Ford Motor  
Co. reached a tentative agreement today on a new contract, hours 
after a handful of workers walked off the job when a strike 
deadline passed. A joint statement announcing the deal contained no 
details. A source close to the talks said the agreement followed 
the pattern set by the UAW in deals with General Motors Corp. and 
DaimlerChrysler AG -- four-year agreements with raises of 3 percent 
each year and a signing bonus. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbine Victim Parents Expand Suit  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- An attorney for the parents of a student killed at  
Columbine High School said today he plans to expand the family's 
wrongful death lawsuit to include at least one gun manufacturer. 
Geoffrey Fieger said Florida-based Navegar and a subsidiary, 
Intratec, which made the TEC-DC9 semiautomatic pistol used during 
the April 20 attack, used marketing strategies designed to make the 
weapon attractive to criminals. Fieger represents Michael and Vonda 
Shoels, whose son Isaiah was among 12 students killed by teen-age 
gunmen Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Chides GOP on Minority Judges  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- President Clinton accused the Republican-led  
Senate of ignoring minority nominees to the federal bench for 
partisan gain, and told Hispanic leaders today that America 
increasingly will ``look like you.'' Clinton said his 
administration has exceeded all others in appointing Hispanic 
judges. But he said too many nominees are languishing in the 
Senate, waiting for approval. ``I am deeply dissatisfied with the 
Senate's partisan handling of some of my minority nominees,'' 
Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Michigan St. Upsets Michigan 34-31  
</P>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Bill Burke passed for a school-record  
400 yards and two touchdowns, and Plaxico Burress caught 10 passes 
for a school-record 255 yards and a score as the No. 11 Spartans 
held off the third-ranked Michigan Wolverines 34-31 today in a 
showdown of Big Ten unbeatens. The win left Michigan State, which 
began the season unranked, 6-0 overall and 3-0 in the conference. 
The Wolverines, hoping for a second national title in three years, 
slipped to 5-1, 2-1. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets, Astros Advance to NLCS  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets beat the Arizona Diamondbacks  
4-3 today and advanced to the National League championship series 
for the first time in 11 years. Todd Pratt homered in the 10th 
inning as the Mets captured the series three games to one. They 
will face the Atlanta Braves, who beat the Houston Astros 7-5 
today, to advance to their eighth straight NLCS. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  














  	   	
</P>
