<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 5 Va. Tech 58, Rutgers 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Michael Vick threw four touchdown passes  
and ran for another in a record-setting performance and No. 5 
Virginia Tech scored TDs on seven of its eight first-half 
possessions in defeating winless Rutgers 58-20 on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The win marked the second straight year that Virginia Tech (5-0,  
1-0 Big East) has opened the second with five straight wins, and it 
set up an interesting matchup next weekend with No. 18 Syracuse 
(5-1) at Blacksburg, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	This marks the second time in three years Rutgers (0-5, 0-2) has  
opened the season with five straight losses under coach Terry Shea. 
The 58 points were the most given up at Rutgers Stadium by the 
Scarlet Knights since the last time the Hokies were here, winning 
59-19 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lopsided score, the game was tied 14-14 after the  
first quarter before Virginia Tech scored 35 unanswered points in 
the second quarter to take command. 
</P>
<P>
	Vick threw a 74-yard scoring pass to a wide-open Andre Davis on  
the opening play from scrimmage. Vick also hit Davis on a 13-yard 
TD to ignite the big second quarter that featured TD passes of 36 
and 5 yards to Ricky Hall, a 2-yard TD run by Shyrone Stith and 
Vick's own 22-yard TD run. 
</P>
<P>
	The four touchdown passes in a half set a school record, while  
the total equalled Virginia Tech's record for a game set previously 
by Don Strock and Maurice DeShazo. 
</P>
<P>
	Vick, who rushd for 68 yards and had 316 yards in total offense,  
broke a Big East Conference record for accuracy hitting 11 of 12 
passes for 248 yards. It broke the old record of 10 of 11 set by 
Rutgers' Ray Lucas in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last two games, Vick has completed 18 of 21 passes for  
470 yards and five touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech gained 420 of its 511 yards in total offense in  
the first half, averaging 10.2 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	After Vick's bomb to a streaking Davis on the opening play,  
Rutgers came right back and tied the score on a 12-yard run by 
quarterback Mike McMahon, who was forced the leave the game late in 
the second quarter with a sprained right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett Ferguson put the Hokies back in front with a 20-yard  
touchdown run before McMahon tied the score again with a 36-yard 
touchdown pass to a wide-open L.J. Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14-14 tie marked the first time this season Virginia Tech  
had not led after the first quarter. That seemed to annoy the 
Hokies and they unloaded on Rutgers in the second quarter for a 
49-14 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Vick didn't leave the bench in the second half.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
