<DOCNO> APW19991009.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 09:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Working Longer Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Vittorio Giulini manages three clothing  
factories, oversees 300 employees and leads a national trade group 
of fashion manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	An American executive with similar duties might expect to work  
60 hours a week, plus a frequent weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so Giulini, of Liola SpA in Milan. He arrives at his office  
at a civilized 9:30 a.m. and knocks off no later than 6:30 p.m. And 
he limits his work week to five days. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saturday and Sunday?'' he asks in disbelief. ``Never.''  
</P>
<P>
	Few Americans flinch at working overtime if it means a bigger  
paycheck. And those striving to build more prosperous lives 
willingly endure long hours and short vacations. 
</P>
<P>
	But millions of Europeans share Giulini's unwillingness to  
forfeit free time, even if it means missing out on an economic boom 
like the one that has enriched so many Americans this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In Europe, dinner each day with the family and a month on the  
Mediterranean each summer are part of a lifestyle too precious to 
sacrifice for the mixed rewards of U.S.-style capitalism. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think industry suffers from that. In the end, you've  
got people who are content and happy in life and do their jobs 
properly when they're at work,'' says Roxanne Suratgar, a market 
analyst for the Italian oil engineering company Snamprogetti. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the World Bank, the United States had an average  
per capita gross national product of $29,080 in 1997, the most 
recent year for which data is available. 
</P>
<P>
	The richest of Europe's biggest economies was France, with an  
average per capita GNP of $22,210, followed in descending order by 
Germany, Britain and Italy. These data were adjusted for 
differences in exchange rates to compare actual purchasing power. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent study suggests, however, that a major reason for the  
higher U.S. income level is simply that Americans work longer hours 
than Europeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans averaged 1,966 hours of work in 1997, according to the  
International Labor Organization, a U.N. agency based in Geneva. 
That's 235 hours more than the British, the hardest-working 
Europeans, and 310 hours, or nearly 39 working days, more than the 
French. 
</P>
<P>
	What's more, Europe is closing its productivity gap with the  
United States even as most Europeans put in fewer hours on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	In France, businesses are beginning to cut their work weeks to  
35 hours in response to a new law introduced by the Socialist-led 
government. Americans, by contrast, worked almost three days more 
in 1997 than in 1990, the ILO said. 
</P>
<P>
	These findings suggest that while Americans may own more cars  
and bigger homes, they have less time to enjoy them. So, who's 
really richer? 
</P>
<P>
	Giulini doesn't hesitate to answer: Europe.  
</P>
<P>
	``The quality of life is higher,'' he says, ``but it's not  
because we are better than Americans. It's because we have 1,000 
years of culture behind us. You can't put a price on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skeptics might dismiss rustic villas and Roman ruins as lifeless  
scenery best suited for postcards. But Italy's teeming cafes and 
entrepreneurs give the place a very contemporary buzz. 
</P>
<P>
	Work habits in Britain are somewhat closer to those of the  
United States, especially in internationally competitive industries 
like banking. Bankers and lawyers in central London's financial 
district work as late into the night as their counterparts on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, professionals in Milan, Italy's commercial hub, are  
usually heading home by 6 or 6:30 p.m., says Suratgar, the market 
analyst, a Briton who has lived in Italy for the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In much of Europe, citizens accept relatively high taxes in  
exchange for governments that provide vibrant cities, first-rate 
public transportation, free universities and bountiful social 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Cafe owner Lena Munther of Stockholm, Sweden, is no better off  
financially than she was at the start of the decade. But the 
Swedish government has helped by easing her burden as the mother of 
a son with a hearing disability. 
</P>
<P>
	Her son Theo, now 20, received special instruction from  
kindergarten through high school, and the government paid for 
soundproof insulation in their home to make it easier for Theo to 
use his hearing aid. 
</P>
<P>
	``All such things were free. I wouldn't have been able to afford  
that if we hadn't had the social system that we have in Sweden,'' 
she says. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to state benefits, European employees generally  
enjoy more job security than workers in the United States. And, 
according to an American executive in Berlin, nonmanagerial staff 
in parts of Europe tend to be better educated and more efficient 
than in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The American, Cary Bruce, is a managing director of Artemedia  
AG, a public relations firm that specializes in virtual reality 
modeling. He has one other observation: 
</P>
<P>
	``This idea that Europeans pack up and go home is more of a myth  
than a reality. Yes, it happens here, but it happens in the U.S., 
too.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 07:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rangers Seem Psyched Out By Yankees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Watching from home last October, Rafael  
Palmeiro couldn't understand how a power-hitting team like the 
Texas Rangers could score just one run in three playoff games 
against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmeiro has figured it out this October, now that he's part of  
a Rangers lineup that has scored just one run in two playoff games 
against the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you think about the hype, the pressure, not scoring runs  
-- then you come to the plate and everything is so huge,'' Palmeiro 
said, spreading his arms wide and leaning back as if he'd been 
shoved. ``Everyone wants to win and is trying to do their best. But 
you can't because there's a big gorilla on your back and it's 
getting heavier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees will try to wrap up the best-of-5 AL divisional  
series tonight at The Ballpark. Should the Rangers win, Game 4 
would be Sunday in Arlington. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has won eight straight playoff games against Texas  
since losing the first meeting in 1996. The Rangers have scored two 
runs in their last 52 postseason innings against the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is getting on Texas for not scoring runs, but  
they're playing a pretty good team and facing a pretty tough 
pitching staff,'' New York first baseman Tino Martinez said. ``I 
think it's more of a matter of us playing well than them choking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Clemens will try to continue the Yankees' run of great  
pitching and move closer to his goal of a World Series 
championship. It's about the only thing missing from his Hall of 
Fame-caliber career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've pretty much accomplished just about anything you would  
want to accomplish in 16 years of doing this,'' said Clemens, a 
five-time Cy Young winner. ``You sit there selfishly saying that, 
but that's the only way you can look at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas starter Esteban Loaiza, the last Rangers pitcher to beat  
the Yankees, will make his first playoff start. It'll be the 10th 
of Clemens' career, but his first in four years. He's looking for 
his first postseason win since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens is coming off a poor season by his standards: 14-10 with  
a career-high 4.60 ERA. He was 1-1 with a 4.96 ERA against the 
Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	New York manager Joe Torre set his rotation so Clemens and David  
Cone, another former Cy Young winner, would pitch on the road. That 
also meant Clemens would get to start before family and friends in 
his home state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pitching in New York, I might not have had the opportunity for  
a lot of my siblings to see it live. As we speak, they're en 
route,'' Clemens said Friday afternoon. ``I've also got some 
college teammates who are going to be in the area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees might not be the same juggernaut that won 114  
regular-season games in 1998, but a victory tonight would put them 
on the same championship pace as their predecessors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers are the victims of bad timing.  
</P>
<P>
	Their three best seasons have come in the last four years, each  
setting up a first-round playoff matchup with New York. The Yankees 
went on to win the World Series the first two times. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's part of the problem,'' Palmeiro said. ``They're the  
best team in baseball over the last four years. If we don't play 
our best, we're not going to beat them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers led the majors with a .293 average and scored 945  
runs, second only to Cleveland. Six players hit 20 home runs, four 
had 100 RBIs and four scored 100 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	But a fifth-inning homer by Juan Gonzalez in Game 2 is Texas'  
only run this series. The Rangers are 0-for-9 with runners in 
scoring position, having failed to score in four situations with 
two on and one out or less. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see frustration on the face of everyone,'' Gonzalez said.  
``We try having fun, being relaxed. It's easy when you talk, but 
it's real hard when you see a lot of zeros on the scoreboard.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
