<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 2 Penn State 31, Iowa 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Two big plays and a goal-line stand  
helped Penn State stay unbeaten. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Drummond ran 68 yards for a touchdown on a reverse and  
Eric McCoo sped 47 yards for another score Saturday, sending the 
No. 2-ranked Nittany Lions to a 31-7 victory over Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than those two plays, Penn State (6-0, 2-0 Big Ten) had to  
scratch and claw for almost everything it got against an Iowa team 
that had been routed by Michigan State 49-3 the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawkeyes (1-4, 0-2) stalled Penn State by intercepting two  
passes and blocking a punt. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a chance to cut the lead to 21-14, Iowa couldn't punch  
it in from the Penn State 1-yard line, and a penalty for having too 
many players on the field led to a 10-yard touchdown run by Aaron 
Harris that clinched it with 10:05 left. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State surprised Iowa with the reverse on its second  
possession. Drummond, flanked to the right, came back to his left 
to take Kevin Thompson's handoff, turned upfield behind excellent 
blocking, dodged a defender at the Iowa 40 and raced down the 
sideline. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa trailed just 14-7 when McCoo broke through a hole in the  
middle of the line, cut to his left and outran the pursuit to the 
end zone, scoring with 4:36 left in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawkeyes got a break a short time later when Ryan Barton  
blocked Pat Pidgeon's punt and Iowa recovered at the Penn State 33. 
Ladell Betts was knocked out of bounds just short of the end zone 
on a 6-yard run, but Penn State held on two straight downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Betts was stopped for a 1-yard loss on third down and Brandon  
Short stopped quarterback Randy Reiners for no gain with an ankle 
tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the Hawkeyes' last gasp. Iowa did stop Penn State on  
third down early in the fourth quarter, but the Hawkeyes had 12 men 
on the field when Penn State punted, giving the Nittany Lions a 
first down at the Iowa 21. Harris scored two plays later to make it 
28-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Forney, who earlier had missed his first field goal  
attempt in eight tries this season, kicked a 26-yarder for the 
final points. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State went up 14-0 at halftime when No. 2 quarterback  
Rashard Casey led a five-play, 63-yard drive that took only 39 
seconds. Casey ran the final 6 yards, slipping into the end zone 
with 9 seconds left in the half as three defenders closed in. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa drew to 14-7 in the third quarter on Reiners' 40-yard  
touchdown pass to fullback Rob Thein, who was wide open when he 
caught the ball in the middle of the field and rumbled into the end 
zone behind Kevin Kasper's block on cornerback Bhawoh Jue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
