<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 09:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Double Murder Conviction Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- She was a wealthy woman, a mother of  
two children, with homes in Taiwan and California. She was also a 
woman betrayed, and in a case that captivated much of Asia, her 
husband helped get her convicted of murdering his mistress and 
child. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, a California court has reversed Li-Yun ``Lisa'' Peng's  
conviction, citing questionable police tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	If the ruling stands, she could walk free after suffering what  
the court called ``repeated, intentional and inexcusable 
deprivation of an individual's most basic constitutional 
protections from coercive tactics by the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My client is very pleased,'' said San Diego lawyer Charles  
Sevilla, who represented her on appeal. ``She's a middle-class mom 
who has been in prison going on six years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crime received little attention in the United States, but  
media from China, Taiwan and elsewhere in Asia had reported every 
detail. A movie about the crime was filmed in Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	Until 1991, electronics tycoon Tseng ``Jim'' Peng and his wife  
were a successful couple, shuttling between Taiwan and a home in 
Rancho Santa Margarita in California's Orange County. They were the 
parents of two sons, and Peng's worth was estimated at $200 
million, most of it from his Ranger Communications which made CB 
radios in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, during a business trip to mainland China, Peng became  
smitten with another woman. He brought 25-year-old Ranbing 
``Jennifer'' Ji to California, set her up in an apartment and gave 
her money to start a business affiliated with his. 
</P>
<P>
	She gave birth to his child, Kevin, in March 1993.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Peng knew of the affair, even met with the mistress and  
threatened her with harm if she did not leave her husband. Once, 
she arrived unexpectedly from Taiwan and found Jim and Jennifer 
staying in her home. She later found the mistress' clothes and cut 
holes in them. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 18, 1993, Jim Peng returned from a trip to Taiwan and  
found his mistress slain, stabbed 19 times and with a bite mark on 
one arm. In a crib in the bedroom of her apartment lay the body of 
5-month-old Kevin, suffocated with a T-shirt stuffed in his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, Jim Peng was the prime suspect, according to court  
papers, but after he passed a polygraph test detectives turned 
their suspicions on his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Peng was found guilty in 1996 after an initial trial ended  
in deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	But the road to that conviction was littered with legal  
violations, the 4th Circuit Court of Appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peng was eager to help Orange County sheriff's deputies. He  
offered a reward, said he would search his wife's financial records 
and went through her wardrobe searching for a button that might 
match one found at the murder scene. 
</P>
<P>
	He persuaded his wife to return to California from Taiwan. With  
no U.S.-Taiwan extradition treaty, Mrs. Peng could have escaped 
prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	After her return in January 1994, Mrs. Peng met with sheriff's  
deputies and was interrogated for nine hours. She was not told of 
her Miranda rights and deputies ignored her request for a lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most fundamental errors in our jurisprudence were made  
during the investigation of this case,'' the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Believing Mrs. Peng was at the breaking point, the decision  
said, deputies brought in her husband to question her in Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	He elicited an admission that she had seen Jennifer the day of  
the killing, they had quarreled and she had bitten Jennifer on one 
arm. DNA tests confirmed the saliva in the bite was hers. That 
became the key evidence against Mrs. Peng, who denied she was the 
murderer. 
</P>
<P>
	In its Sept. 30 ruling, the appeals court called the statement  
coerced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even an innocent person would make some kind of statement  
potentially incriminating after nine hours of threats, intimidation 
and bullying by law enforcement officers in the bowels of a county 
jail and then being confronted with the questions of the victim's 
paramour,'' the court said. ``The statements should have been 
suppressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case was sent back to the trial court for retrial, unless  
the prosecution decides to drop the charges or appeal to a higher 
state court. Pending a decision, Mrs. Peng remains in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant Sheriff Tim Simon disputed the ruling, saying he and  
prosecutors will review it before deciding what to do with the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Weisselberg, a law professor at the University of  
California, Berkeley, said that unless detectives find more 
evidence, it would be a difficult case. 
</P>
<P>
	And the court concluded: ``Her statements were brutally  
damaging; without it her guilt was barely even insinuated.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
