<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citizen's Revolt Now A Barbecue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JARBIDGE, Nev. (AP) -- It was supposed to be a citizens' revolt:  
Some 1,000 people armed with tools, rebuilding a remote mountain 
road despite government warnings that it would threaten an 
endangered fish species. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a judge ruled against today's planned reconstruction,  
protesters decided to do something a little less contentious -- hold 
a barbecue and rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not defy the order,'' state Assemblyman John Carpenter  
said Friday, just hours after vowing to defy U.S. District Judge 
David Hagen's decision. ``We will not break the law. The work party 
has been canceled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute involves a 1 1/2-mile section of road that leads to a  
campground and outhouse in the Humboldt Toiyabe-National Forest. 
Elko County and the federal government have been odds since a flood 
washed the road out in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service decided not to rebuild the road because  
eroding soil could foul the river and threaten the bull trout, now 
protected under the Endangered Species Act. 
</P>
<P>
	But Carpenter had planned to lead citizens of this remote  
historic mining town with pickaxes and shovels to start 
reconstruction this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	At the request of the U.S. Attorney's Office, Hagen issued a  
temporary restraining order late Thursday blocking the action. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our hope this project wouldn't happen because it would  
impact the bull trout,'' said Fish and Wildlife spokeswoman Randi 
Thompson. ``It's spawning time and a very tenuous time for the 
fish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said her agency hoped to re-open talks with Elko County to  
resume working toward a reasonable alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	If any trout were harmed, Thompson said the group could face  
fines of $12,000 per fish in civil penalties and $25,000 per fish 
in criminal penalties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
