<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 11:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Going for Mattel's Barad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- For nearly two years Mattel Inc. chief  
Jill E. Barad dazzled Wall Street with a flashy style and marketing 
savvy that helped turn the toymaker into a worldwide powerhouse 
with brands such as Barbie and Hot Wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	To many, she seemed the perfect leader for the world's largest  
toy company. Her enthusiasm and energy appeared boundless. Clad in 
smart, designer clothes, she promoted Mattel with gusto, sometimes 
even dancing to the music that blared out in meetings where new 
toys were unveiled to industry analysts and investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``My impression of her is that she is the consummate product  
person, that she loves the product,'' toy consultant Chris Byrne 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But investors haven't shared that enthusiasm during the past  
year. For the second time in 10 months, Wall Street has been 
shocked by surprise announcements that Mattel can't live up to 
revenue estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	The news earlier this week pushed the company's stock to its  
lowest point since 1993, with shares trading Friday at $11.81 1/4, 
down 50 cents. It's off nearly 75 percent from a 10-year high of 
$46.75 reached last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest miscalculation -- which has already generated two  
class-action suits by investors -- has left some analysts wondering 
if Barad is up to the job of turning Mattel around, or if she will 
even be given the chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The board is faced with a tough situation. Do they make a  
management change or shuffle before their most important season of 
the year?'' said Eric Gustafson, a senior portfolio manager at 
Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressure on Barad intensified this week after Mattel revealed  
that The Learning Company, a software maker acquired by Mattel in 
May for $3.8 billion, will lose up to $100 million in the third 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The board appears to be willing to give Barad time. Barad met  
with directors on Wednesday in New York, telling members she had 
been advised of The Learning Company's troubles late last week and 
was trying to learn the cause of the problem, according to a source 
familiar with the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	A Mattel spokesman declined to comment Friday, except to say  
Barad continued to have the full support of Mattel's board. 
</P>
<P>
	Barad, 48, took the helm of Mattel in January 1997, capping a  
16-year climb that began in the company's novelty toy unit. Under 
her supervision, Barbie was transformed from a tired, $200 million 
product line into one of the world's most recognized brands with 
$1.9 billion in sales last year. 
</P>
<P>
	And she seems to recognize the changing desires of kids today,  
who are more interested in high-tech toys by the age of 6 rather 
than playing with dolls and board games. Mattel's has stepped up 
its software and online offerings, and looked to new avenues to 
capture shoppers. 
</P>
<P>
	As Mattel's chairman and chief executive, Barad underwent a  
transformation of sorts. The one-time actress and beauty consultant 
-- one of only three women currently running a Fortune 500 company -- 
became a role model for millions of working women trying to break 
into the ranks of corporate management. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street's romance with Barad and Mattel turned rocky last  
December after Mattel announced a $500 million shortfall for 1998 -- 
a disclosure came only weeks after a series of meetings in which 
Barad assured analysts that Mattel would meet its revenue 
projections. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel made a mistake when it based its original projections on  
the number of orders the company received in previous years, 
analysts said. Mattel ignored an announcement by Toys R Us, a key 
customer, that it planned to reduce its inventory during the year, 
and the prospect that other retailers would do likewise. 
</P>
<P>
	What went wrong with The Learning Company is less clear. The two  
problems are similar, though, in that Mattel appears to have been 
oblivious to the problem until the last minute. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are to believe everything, it would appear they were  
totally out of the loop on what was going on with this latest 
acquisition,'' said Margaret Whitfield, an analyst at Tucker 
Anthony. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattel is blaming the shortfall on a variety of problems,  
including the loss of a key distribution deal, an unexpectedly high 
return of unsold product from retailers and the write-off of bad 
debts. The explanation is disturbing to analysts because it 
suggests that The Learning Company was depending on a one-time cash 
payment from the distribution deal to make ends meet. 
</P>
<P>
	The larger question is why Mattel was in the dark. Officials at  
the software maker, like those heading other Mattel product lines, 
report directly to Barad. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the problems with The Learning Company were pointed out  
in a July report on Mattel issued by the Center for Financial 
Research and Analysis. Analyst Sirine Hafez reported The Learning 
Company's sales in the first half of 1999 fell well below 1998 
levels. There was also a big jump in accounts receivables, or money 
owed the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a good acquisition. That's where the problem lies,''  
said Jim Silver, editor of The Toy Book, an industry publication. 
``The rest of Mattel is fine. (The Learning Company) is one big 
problem, though.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 10:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush's Slogan Has Family Roots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is taking pains in  
politics to be his own man, but a new biography says the Republican 
presidential candidate is using a slogan that was applied to his 
father. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compassionate conservative'' was used by Ron Kaufman, an aide  
to the senior Bush when he was running for president in the 
mid-1980s, in a Christian magazine article designed to make 
religious conservatives comfortable with the candidate, the 
biography says. 
</P>
<P>
	``First Son: George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty,'' was  
released Sunday. The book, the first in a new series of competing 
biographies coming out on the GOP front-runner, was written by Bill 
Minutaglio, a Dallas Morning News reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	The evenhanded book leaves unsettled two questions from the  
governor's past. It avoids any ``dollops of drug tales'' -- the 
long-standing, still-unsubstantiated speculation about whether the 
younger Bush ever used illegal drugs; and it offers no proof his 
family pulled strings to keep him out of the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	``First Son'' details Bush's time living in Washington when he  
served as ``loyalty monitor'' in his father's presidential 
campaign. He was also the family's liaison with ascendant leaders 
of the religious right, who worried the vice president was not 
nearly as in tune with their issues as President Reagan was. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1986, the month the younger Bush suddenly stopped his  
years of hard drinking, the evangelical magazine Christian Herald 
published a cover story written by a Bush campaign aide in which 
Kaufman, head of the vice president's political action committee, 
said the candidate was best described as a ``compassionate 
conservative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The phrase gained limited currency in the 1988 campaign. It was  
used to describe both the vice president and a rival for the GOP 
nomination that year, Bob Dole. Indeed, Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch 
of Utah, now running against the younger Bush, called himself a 
compassionate conservative way back in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the slogan is at the core of the governor's campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	The book says that once the vice president won the election, his  
son helped hand out political favors. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Minutaglio writes, the younger Bush suggested a  
wealthy Texas publisher, Roger Horchow, be appointed chairman of 
the National Endowment for the Arts because he had given money to 
the Bush campaign. But when aides discovered the publisher had also 
contributed to Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis, he scratched 
his name from the list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Transportation Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed a $50 billion  
transportation bill into law Saturday, a wide-ranging measure 
funding transit and infrastructure projects, Amtrak and the Coast 
Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, includes $26.7  
billion for highways, a 10 percent increase from last year, and 
$5.8 billion for mass transit programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe these funding levels will allow us to make the  
substantial improvements in infrastructure and mass transit that 
are necessary,'' White House spokesman Jake Siewert said. 
</P>
<P>
	It also provides $571 million for Amtrak, including funds for a  
five-year plan to get the national passenger railroad operating 
self-sufficiently and eliminate the need for year-to-year 
subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	It contains all the money Clinton requested for Coast Guard  
operating expenses, $2.8 billion, including search and rescue 
operations and increased spending for law enforcement and drug 
interdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	And it extends for one year a restraint on the government's use  
of new automobile fuel efficiency standards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
