<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 11:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Gives Redskins Boost at QB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- With a cigar in his hand and a million  
stories to tell, Hall of Fame quarterback Sonny Jurgensen is a 
fixture at Redskin Park, an unofficial adviser for coaches and 
players -- especially quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurgensen's wisdom was much-needed in recent years as Heath  
Shuler and Gus Frerotte failed to master coach Norv Turner's 
complex game plans. Mondays seemed like an endless critical review 
of what went wrong -- until Brad Johnson showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Washington Redskins quarterback has been almost perfect.  
</P>
<P>
	``What does he need to ask me questions for?'' Jurgensen said.  
``He's playing as well as the position can be played.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the bye week after four games, Johnson is having an MVP  
season. That's not just because of his incredible stats -- he might 
single-handedly save the jobs of most of the employees in the 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	If Johnson leads the Redskins (3-1) to the playoffs, new owner  
Dan Snyder might not fire the coaching staff and clean house. And 
if Johnson and the league's top-ranked offense continue to put up 
37 1/2 points and 412 1/2 yards per game, he'll help hide the 
embarrassment of a defense allowing a league-worst 29 1/2 points and 
433 1/2 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first two years here, I thought we had a quarterback,''  
defensive end Kenard Lang said. ``Until I saw Brad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brimming with composure and confidence, Johnson has completed 63  
percent of his passes and has nine touchdowns with no 
interceptions. His 119.9 rating is second to Kurt Warner of the St. 
Louis Rams. Neither Shuler nor Frerotte ever led the Redskins to a 
fourth-quarter comeback victory; Johnson has done it two straight 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows what he's doing and he takes control,'' Jurgensen  
said. ``He's a leader on the field. That's something the Redskins 
haven't had offensively in the last five or six years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins are playing wild football, with final scores of  
41-35, 50-21, 27-20 and 38-36. It's easy to panic when the fourth 
quarter gets crazy, but that's when Johnson seems to thrive. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're up in the stands, you feel your hands are sweaty,''  
Johnson said, reflecting the game-winning drive in last week's 
38-36 win over Carolina. ``I had 10 people call me on the cell 
phone after the game, and eight of them said they about had a heart 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it's a different feeling. Things were slow. I felt  
very comfortable. It seemed like in that last drive, everything 
kind of slowed down. I hit a few game-winning jump shots in high 
school. You want to define the moment, but you don't want to say 
your whole livelihood's on this one play, one drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it is something kind of special.''  
</P>
<P>
	When the Redskins traded three drafts picks to Minnesota for  
Johnson in February, the big concern was his durability after an 
injury-riddled season with the Vikings. Johnson had surgery on his 
knee in May, still ices it down two to three hours a day and was 
given less work this week in practice to help ease the soreness. 
</P>
<P>
	But the injury hasn't been noticeable during games. Johnson has  
an uncanny ability to step out of the way of a blitz at the last 
possible second. Johnson has been sacked a half-dozen times this 
season, but his deft footwork has prevented at least a half-dozen 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that has impressed me about him is his awareness in  
the pocket,'' Jurgensen said, ``in feeling the rush and avoiding 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turner also likes to talk about Johnson's awareness in the  
pocket. Watching the films, the coach notes how Johnson surveys the 
field while dropping back to pass, rather than waiting until he's 
in the pocket. That's not too difficult when the receivers are 
running short patterns, but Johnson can take in more than one 
option and still go deep without messing up the timing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have, in the past, gotten people open,'' Turner said.  
``When we get someone open now, he doesn't miss him. I don't think 
there are many people who throw the ball deep as accurately as Brad 
does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At age 31, Johnson's strength is his experience, but he still  
had to undergo some basic training when he arrived in Washington. 
As someone who made his name tutoring quarterbacks, specifically 
Dallas' Troy Aikman, Turner wants every mechanical part of the play 
to be perfect. The three-step drop, for example, must consist of 
one big step and two little steps -- and they must be done right. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very organized, the most organized person I've ever been  
around,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback, in return, is helping to save Turner's  
reputation, which was hurt after his failures with Shuler and 
Frerotte and a bad breakup with veteran backup Jeff Hostetler last 
year. If the Redskins end their six-year postseason drought, the 
bulk of the thank-yous -- including the coach's -- will belong to 
Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he's done,'' Jurgensen said, ``is make everybody else  
better.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
