<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 1 FSU 31, No. 19 Miami 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Football Writer-    	
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Peter Warrick wasn't around, so Chris  
Weinke simply went to the next best option, and wide receiver Ron 
Dugans came through to bail out No. 1 Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	Dugans turned a short pass into a 54-yard gain to set up Travis  
Minor's fourth-quarter 2-yard touchdown run that lifted the 
Seminoles to a 31-21 victory over No. 19 Miami on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick, the Heisman Trophy favorite serving an indefinite  
suspension after his arrest on a grand theft charge of underpaying 
for designer clothes at a department store, watched his team 
struggle for three quarters before winning its 27th straight at 
Doak Campbell Stadium and 44th without a loss. Both streaks are the 
longest among major colleges. 
</P>
<P>
	Dugans wasn't the only receiver who came to Weinke's rescue. In  
completing 23-of-34 for 332 yards, Weinke had first-half TD passes 
of 48 yards to seldom-used Germaine Stringer and 18 yards to tight 
end Ryan Sprague. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State (6-0) has now beaten Miami (2-3) four years in a  
row, but this one was the toughest yet, especially without Warrick, 
who averages 154 all-purpose yards per game. Dressed in baggy blue 
jeans and a red golf shirt, Warrick paced the sideline cheering on 
his team and hoping his legal problems are cleared up next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami quarterback Kenny Kelly was sensational, hitting 27-of-41  
passes for 370 yards and three touchdowns, including two to Santana 
Moss, one an 80-yarder that tied the score 14-14 after one quarter. 
Moss finished with nine catches for 180 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Seminoles ahead 24-21 on Sebastian Janikowski's 38-yard  
field goal midway through the third quarter, Weinke led the 
Seminoles on a game-clinching 97-yard drive. After Dugans' 54-yard 
gain to the Miami 30, FSU moved down to the 13, when Miami's 
Leonard Myers was called for pass interference in the end zone 
against Dugans. 
</P>
<P>
	On the next play, from the Miami 3, Minor powered into the end  
zone and Florida State kept its national title hopes alive as 
80,976 fans broke into the Seminole War Chant. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor had 25 carries for 146 yards, with Dugans finishing with  
five catches for 80 yards and Stringer had three catches for 80 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without Warrick, the first half was filled with big plays --  
by both teams. Fittingly, it was 21-21 after 30 minutes, with the 
Hurricanes keeping the pressure on a shaky Florida State secondary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles opened a 7-0 lead on their second possession when  
Stringer, one of two replacements for Warrick, caught his 48-yard 
TD pass just 3:47 into the game. He beat Myers on a post pattern, 
caught the ball in stride at the 13 and scored untouched. When he 
returned to the bench, he was greeted by a towel-waving Warrick. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami, the last team to beat Florida State at Doak Campbell (in  
1991), wasted little time in pulling even. 
</P>
<P>
	King threw an 8-yard scoring pass to Reggie Wayne 3:08 later,  
the football sailing over the head of cornerback Mario Edwards in 
the left corner of the end zone and into the Hurricane receiver's 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles moved ahead 14-7, on Jeff Chaney's 3-yard TD run,  
and the Hurricanes responded on Kelly's 80-yard TD pass to Moss. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles lost a scoring chance late in the first quarter  
when Dan Kendra fumbled at the Miami 10 and the Hurricanes Al 
Blades recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami took a 21-14 lead after an 89-yard march, with Kelly  
hitting Moss on a 6-yard TD, with Edwards again the beaten defender 
in the end zone. This time it was the Seminoles turn to even the 
score, with Weinke finding Sprauge behind Miami's linebackers on 
the 18-yard scoring pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments before kickoff, both teams had to be restrained from  
going at each other at midfield. One of the Miami players shouted 
something to a Florida State player, and both teams gathered near 
midfield, each forming a huge circle. All the players began jumping 
up and down in unison, jawing at each other, before coaches came 
over and broke things up. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
