<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Protesters Snub Cuban Band </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A performance by one of Cuba's hottest bands drew  
thousands of anti-Castro protesters to Miami Arena Saturday night, 
with many waving flags, shouting slogans and denouncing the show. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, believed to number between 4,000 to 7,500,  
outnumbered concertgoers, who numbered from 3,000 to 5,000, 
according to unofficial estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	After more than two hours of Afro-Cuban dance music by the  
popular group Los Van Van, ticket holders were escorted past 
jeering, refuse-throwing protesters angered that musicians popular 
in the Communist nation were allowed to perform in the heart of the 
Cuban exile community. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in riot gear kept the two sides from each other, and no  
clashes were reported after the concert. 
</P>
<P>
	After being warmly welcomed elsewhere during a tour of the  
United States, Los Van Van got the cold shoulder in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrators carried signs reading ``Castro: 40 years of  
dictatorship and 40 years of slavery'' and ``Van: Get out of 
Miami.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing against the music they play,'' said protester  
Luis Eseandal. ``This is about the Cuban government and Fidel 
Castro. That's why we're here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, a brief disturbance broke out between police and  
protesters when about a dozen demonstrators hopped the steel 
barricades and tried to run to the entrance of the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Police used pepper spray to control the rowdy group, and a  
handful of protesters were led away in handcuffs as supporters 
shouted their outrage. 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter was treated for a minor cut after being hit in the  
head by a rock. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of Miami's Cuban-American community denounced Los  
Van Van as emissaries of Cuban President Fidel Castro, and the 
appearance got canceled, only to be rescheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not telling the truth,'' said protester Mirta  
Oliva-Rios. ``This group is a representative of Fidel Castro. We 
don't need that here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and city Commissioner Tomas Regalado,  
both Cuban-born, last month vented their objections to the concert 
on Spanish-language radio, and the dispute generated thousands of 
calls to city hall. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union threatened to sue after the  
show's cancellation at another city-owned venue. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterans of the failed 1961 Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba showed  
an anti-Castro film Saturday night a few blocks away, at the James 
L. Knight Center, the original site of the Los Van Van show, then 
made their way to the Arena to protest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban exile group Democracy Movement issued a statement  
Saturday objecting to the ``insincerity'' of allowing Los Van Van 
to perform. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both sides pretend for us to accept on its face value their  
claim that they are leading a 'people to people contact' policy 
when in reality, Castro's Van come to Miami to play while our 
Gloria Estefan, Celia Cruz or Willie Chirino cannot go to Cuba to 
do the same,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Formell, who founded Los Van Van 30 years ago, rejected the  
label applied by opponents who call the group the ``official'' band 
of the Cuban government. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't do politics. We make music,'' Formell said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cultural exchange exemptions under the U.S. trade embargo allow  
Cuban bands to perform in the United States if they don't profit 
from the concerts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991009.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 15:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenwood Lake Wins at Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Greenwood Lake likes to do it his way -- and that  
way is unnerving for a trainer and owner. 
</P>
<P>
	It also was the winning way Saturday as the colt came from way  
out of it to win the 1 1-16-mile Champagne for 2-year-olds at 
Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why he takes himself back, but that's the way he  
likes to run,'' trainer Nick Zito said after his second straight 
victory in the Champagne. He won with The Groom Is Red last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just know he's not going to make it; he's too far back,''  
co-owner Joseph Cornacchia said of Greenwood Lake, who was last in 
the seven-horse field for the first three-quarters of a mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Jean-Luc Samyn, Greenwood Lake was 9 lengths behind  
with a little more than a quarter-mile remaining, but he was 2 1/2 
lengths ahead at the wire after charging past Chief Seattle with 
about 30 yards remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	In the race following the Champagne, Val's Prince took the lead  
just inside the eighth pole and won the 1 1/2-mile Turf Classic by a 
length over Dream Well for his second straight victory in a Grade I 
stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	While Greenwood Lake raced into the 2-year-old championship  
picture, favored More Than Ready finished a dismal fifth for his 
second straight loss after five straight victories that had made 
him the division leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwood Lake, winning for the second time in four starts,  
carried home scale weight of 122 pounds in 1:43 3-5 and paid 
$15.60, $5.10 and $3.20. He earned $240,000 from a $400,000 purse 
for owners Cornacchia, Dolores Conway and Fred Dematteis. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Seattle paid $3.90 and $3, and High Yield returned $2.60  
for show. 
</P>
<P>
	Val's Prince, who won the Man o'War in his previous start,  
marked himself as the serious contender for the $2 million 
Breeders' Cup Turf on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park. Yagli, the 8-5 
favorite, was trapped on the hedge in the stretch and wasn't a 
factor in his second straight defeat after having won three 
straight stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Val's Prince, a 7-year-old gelding owned by Weiner Martin,  
carried home 126 in 2:28 3-5 and earned $360,000 from a purse of 
$600,000. He paid $8.10, $3.80 and $3. He is trained by James Bond, 
trainer of Behrens, the favorite for the $1 million Jockey Club 
Gold Cup Sunday at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought Val's Prince was the best turf horse in the  
country, Bond said, ``He sure looks that way to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	France-based Dream Well, making his U.S. debut, returned $4.10  
and $3.60 after finishing neck in front of Fahris in the 
seven-horse field. Fahris paid $5.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
