<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Brett on Rockies' List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Recent Hall of Fame inductee George Brett, the  
Kansas City Royals vice president of operations, is a candidate to 
replace Jim Leyland as manager of the Colorado Rockies, The Denver 
Post reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Dan O'Dowd, the Rockies new general manager, said  
Cincinnati Reds director of player development, Buddy Bell, remains 
the top candidate to replace Leyland who retired after one season 
in which Colorado finished 72-90, last in the NL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, George Brett is an outstanding baseball person,''  
O'Dowd said. ``But to say anything more would be inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies need to get permission from the Royals to interview  
Brett, who has no coaching or managing experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing I've realized is that since I retired from baseball  
five years ago, I do miss it,'' the 46-year-old Brett said Friday 
from his suburban Kansas City home. ``I haven't done much in those 
five years, and I'm a very competitive person. I haven't been 
connected to any real business ventures. I feel my life slipping 
away a little bit. 
</P>
<P>
	``So after five years of slipping, I'm obviously very flattered  
that the Rockies have enough respect for me to consider me for such 
an important position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other candidates being interviewed besides Bell and Brett  
include Rockies coaches Clint Hurdle and Rich Donnelly, and 
Cleveland hitting coach Charlie Manuel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
