<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 21:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers' Sluggers Silenced by N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- The Texas Rangers exited the 1999 AL  
playoffs just as they had in their two previous playoff appearances 
-- with scarcely a whimper. 
</P>
<P>
	The AL West champs, who hit a major league-high .293 and scored  
945 runs during a 95-victory regular season, were the same old 
Rangers in the playoffs, unnerved and outclassed by the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas' lineup provided another futile performance Saturday  
night, managing only five hits against Roger Clemens and two 
relievers as the Yankees completed a three-game sweep of the first 
round with a 3-0 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second consecutive year, Texas scored only one run in  
three games against New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no jinx,'' said Rafael Palmeiro, who went 3-for-11 --  
all singles -- after hitting .324 with 47 homers and 148 RBIs during 
the season. ``You can say whatever. We didn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't as good as I tried to be and I wasn't as good as I  
wanted to be,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers hit .141 in last year's sweep and batted just .152  
(14-for-92) this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sheer fact that people are thinking they have to do  
something different causes them to press and squeeze the bat,'' 
said Todd Zeile, who went 0-for-3 and grounded out to end the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what I saw in New York. Once we started falling behind,  
we felt the weight of the monkey, which has turned into a 400-pound 
gorilla,'' he said. ``We've said try a little easier. You have to 
relax to be successful at this level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once again, Rangers pitching was good enough to win if only the  
bats had shown up. Starter Esteban Loaiza gave up a three-run homer 
to Darryl Strawberry in the first, but shut New York out on three 
hits before giving way to reliever Jeff Zimmerman in the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	As they had in the first two games, Rangers hitters made it easy  
on New York by showing little patience. The Yankees outscored Texas 
14-1 in the sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a few months to analyze what happened this playoff  
and see how we can score at will pretty much in the season and then 
in three games not even smell home plate,'' Texas manager Johnny 
Oates said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think sometimes we got confused,'' he said. ``We had a bunch  
of people telling people to be more patient, be more patient. ... 
We did something right for the first 162 games. Now, why did we 
have to change it for the next three?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas' first at-bat with a runner in scoring position came in  
the fourth, when Lee Stevens grounded out weakly on the first 
pitch. The next Texas baserunner was Rusty Greer, who walked in the 
sixth. Slugger Juan Gonzalez followed with a dribbler to first and 
Palmeiro ended the inning by grounding Clemens' second pitch back 
to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Goodwin opened the eighth with a single off Jeff Nelson.  
Mariano Rivera came on and got Mark McLemore to line into a double 
play and struck out Ivan Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	Greer led off the ninth with a single and went to second on a  
wild pitch. Gonzalez flied out, Palmeiro popped out and Zeile made 
the final out. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas' vanishing offense has already become a tradition in the  
team's brief playoff history. 
</P>
<P>
	Since a 6-2 victory over the Yankees in Game 1 of the 1996  
division series -- the first postseason game in team history -- the 
Rangers have lost nine consecutive playoff games to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In nearly all the losses, Texas has been virtually unable to  
touch Yankees pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	New York manager Joe Torre said what many at The Ballpark were  
thinking: ``Obviously, when they've had trouble beating us, you 
know there's a psychological thing going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deep freeze affected even the Rangers' best hitters. Greer,  
a career .309 hitter, hit .091 in 1998's playoff disaster and had 
just one hit this series. Gonzalez, a two-time AL MVP, went 
1-for-12 in last year's series and 2-for-11 this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough,'' Greer said. ``You work all year to get there,  
then it's three and you're out.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
