<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 9, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Ford, UAW Reach Tentative Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- The United Auto Workers and Ford Motor  
Co. reached a tentative agreement Saturday on a new contract, hours 
after a handful of workers walked off the job when a strike 
deadline passed. A local union official in Tulsa, Okla., said the 
agreement allowed the spin-off of Visteon Automotive Systems, 
Ford's parts division. UAW officials have said they were opposed to 
the company's plans for Visteon, which employs 23,500 UAW workers. 

</P>
<P>
	Boris Yeltsin Hospitalized With Flu  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- After months of relatively stable health,  
President Boris Yeltsin was rushed to a hospital Saturday with what 
doctors said was the flu and a very high fever. Yeltsin, 68, was 
resting in Moscow's Central Clinical hospital, where doctors were 
working to bring down his temperature, presidential spokesman 
Dmitry Yakushkin said. The Kremlin said the situation was not 
serious. 

</P>
<P>
	321 Dead in Mexico Floods  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico (AP) -- In all, at least 321 people have been  
confirmed dead in last week's flooding in Mexico, which President 
Ernesto Zedillo called the country's worst disaster this decade. 
But as flood victims across southeastern Mexico urged the president 
to call for foreign aid, Zedillo assured them ``the Mexicans can do 
it alone.'' Mexican soldiers used picks, shovels and sledgehammers 
Saturday in search of dozens of bodies believed buried in a massive 
mudslide. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Suggests Bradley Abandoned Democrats  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Al Gore and Bill Bradley tangled over  
their political loyalties Saturday in a rare showdown of Democratic 
presidential candidates, with the vice president suggesting his 
rival abandoned the party in its darkest hours. Specifically, Gore 
criticized Bradley for leaving the Senate in 1996, two years after 
Republicans won control of Congress. ``I've always been a Democrat 
since I cast my first vote in 1964,'' said Bradley, who has 
suggested that Gore's centrist politics undermine his claim to the 
Democratic mantle. While Gore has the backing of much of the 
party's establishment, a poll last week showed Bradley within a 
dozen points of Gore in Iowa. 

</P>
<P>
	Families Join Reno on Hate Crimes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The families of hate-crime victims Matthew  
Shepard and James Byrd Jr. appeared with Attorney General Janet 
Reno on Saturday night as part of a campaign to persuade Congress 
to include attacks on gays and lesbians among federal hate crimes. 
Gay rights advocates say the Byrd family's presence was key to 
building support for the Hate Crimes Prevention Act, which has been 
passed by the Senate and must still be considered by the House. 

</P>
<P>
	Rail Unions Criticize London Co.  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Rail unions expressed disgust when they learned  
that some of the train cars involved in Tuesday's deadly crash had 
been salvaged from another crash two years ago. Deputy Prime 
Minister John Prescott announced an investigation into rail safety 
under Railtrack, the company that owns and operates Britain's 
formerly nationalized rail service. At least 40 people perished 
Tuesday when two passenger trains collided two miles west of 
London's Paddington Station, Scotland Yard said. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Advance to AL Championships  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry hit a three-run homer  
in the first inning and Roger Clemens made it stand up Saturday 
night, sending the New York Yankees into the AL championship series 
with a 3-0 victory over the Texas Rangers that capped a first-round 
sweep. New York will start the ALCS at home Wednesday night against 
the winner of the Cleveland-Boston series. The Indians, whom the 
Yankees beat in six games last year on their way to the World 
Series title, lead the Red Sox 2-1. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Win; Mets, Braves Advance  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The New York Mets and the Atlanta Braves advanced  
to the National League Championship Series today while the Boston 
Red Sox avoided first-round sweep in the American League playoffs. 
The Mets' Todd Pratt homered in the 10th inning for a 4-3 win over 
Arizona as New York took the series three games to one. In Houston, 
the Braves clinched its opening-round series with a 7-5 victory 
over the Astros. In Boston, the Red Sox beat the Cleveland Indians 
9-3 behind a strong pitching performance from Ramon Martinez. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 21 Ohio St. Edges No. 17 Purdue  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Brent Johnson blocked a potential tying  
field goal with 53 seconds left and Steve Bellisari's late 68-yard 
run preserved the lead as No. 21 Ohio State held off No. 17 Purdue 
25-22 today. Ohio State took the lead for good on Jonathan Wells' 
2-yard run with 5:13 remaining. Purdue quarterback Drew Brees, 
heralded as a Heisman Trophy contender, completed 24 of 39 passes 
for 205 yards and was held without a touchdown pass for the first 
time in 19 games. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  



  	   	
</P>
