<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 01:50:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanic Meeting on Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The numbers are clear -- if not a bit astounding.  
</P>
<P>
	Hispanics now make up about 11 percent of the U.S. population,  
half of them younger than age 20. That means that by 2050, one of 
every four Americans will be of Hispanic descent, according to U.S. 
Census estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	With such figures in mind, Hispanic leaders are eager to groom  
young talent to add political clout to their numbers. Some of the 
most prominent leaders are meeting here this weekend, at the U.S. 
Hispanic Leadership Conference, to find it. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 8,000 people -- most of them between the ages of 18  
and 34 -- have signed up for the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to high school students Friday, former Housing  
Secretary Henry Cisneros said that because the Hispanic population 
is expected to grow so much in their lifetimes, a great deal of 
responsibility is on them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not want us to be a poor, hostile, angry, uneducated  
population in America. ... You can be the ones to break the 
pattern,'' he said. ``Can you do it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the students broke into uproarious applause.  
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros is now head of Univision, a major Spanish-language  
television network. He was one of many Hispanic leaders who 
encouraged conference attendees to go to college, register to vote 
and organize politically -- all goals backed up at the conference by 
workshops and a college and job fair. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to keep people accountable,'' said Cisneros. ``We  
also, from time to time, have to defend ourselves when people come 
after us just because we are Latino.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Cisneros, officials attending the conference  
included everyone from Aida Alvarez, head of the U.S. Small 
Business Administration, to Raymond Anrecio, a manager at General 
Motors' Public Policy Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being here, I feel everyone is a role model. All of them give  
me good goals,'' said Davina Gonzalez, an 18-year-old high school 
senior from Santa Ana, Calif., one of many to swarm Cisneros to get 
photos or autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez -- who wants to be a child psychologist and made her  
first plane trip to take part in the conference -- said being chosen 
to participate was inspiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me very proud. It makes me feel like I will be able  
to be happy -- to live in a nice house with a yard, to have a family 
and to be able to buy them things they need,'' she said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
