<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India PM Seeking Consensus on Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Fresh from his solid election victory,  
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India said he will seek a 
consensus among all parties to bring about economic and political 
changes, a newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee's immediate concern will be to persuade opposition  
parties to allow India to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, 
which successive governments have opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	His 13-month-old administration, which collapsed in April, also  
was unable to push through key bills to allow foreign insurance 
companies to set up shop in India after opposition parties stalled 
a vote in parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time that the bitterness generated during the elections  
subsides. It is time that we created an atmosphere of consensus,'' 
Vajpayee told The Times of India newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The monthlong general elections were marked by bitter personal  
attacks, especially concerning the Italian ancestry of Vajpayee's 
main rival, Sonia Gandhi of the Congress party. Mrs. Gandhi, in 
turn, accused Vajpayee's Bharatiya Janata Party of whipping up 
attacks on Muslim and Christian minorities and called his allies 
political opportunists. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee will be formally elected leader of his 22-party  
National Democratic Alliance on Sunday and he will then meet 
President K.R. Narayanan a day later to stake his claim to form the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee faces the daunting task of pleasing all his allies in  
distributing Cabinet portfolios. Several parties have already 
sought key jobs for their lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview, Vajpayee said his government would like to  
quickly pass pending bills to reform the insurance sector, curb 
money laundering and streamline laws relating to foreign exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest election, which concluded last week, Vajpayee's  
coalition won a clear majority, raising hopes that India would have 
a stable government for the first time in years. Four minority 
governments have fallen in three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
