<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-09 05:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Soldiers Test Australians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Indonesian commandos have been carrying  
out patrols and probing the military capabilities of the 
Australian-led peacekeeping force, members of the force say, 
raising concern that such covert operations might lead to clashes. 
</P>
<P>
	The commandos are actively reconnoitering positions held by the  
peacekeeping force along the frontier separating East Timor, which 
has voted overwhelmingly for independence, and Indonesian-held West 
Timor, said foreign peacekeeping officers on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Such activity is often a prelude to an attack.  
</P>
<P>
	Several groups of soldiers, believed to be part of Indonesia's  
elite Kopassus special forces brigade, were observed conducting 
nighttime patrols around the foreign troops' positions near the 
town of Balibo this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were definitely soldiers, not militia,'' said Australian  
army Capt. Grant King on Thursday. King was on duty in Balibo and 
debriefed troops who spotted the infiltrators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australians held their fire and the patrols eventually  
slipped back across the border to West Timor, he said. Australian 
soldiers on the spot confirmed that the patrols appeared to have 
been mounted by Kopassus troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeepers noted that the men were equipped with body  
armor, night-vision scopes and sophisticated automatic weapons 
issued only to Indonesian army elite troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The commander of the peacekeepers force, Australian Maj. Gen.  
Peter Cosgrove, today warned groups prowling around near his troops 
not to attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should not think they are unobserved. They should not  
think they are not vulnerable to a sanction if they were to take 
aggressive action,'' Cosgrove said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian generals have made extensive use of the crack  
Kopassus unit in recent years, particularly in a campaign to stamp 
out a separatist rebel movement in Aceh, the country's westernmost 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	Although military analysts say its capabilities are limited --  
particularly when facing a modern, Western force such as the 
Australian army -- the brigade is the best that Indonesian has. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia has developed detailed information on the operations  
of the Indonesian military through years of military cooperation 
and intelligence gathering with its northern neighbor. Before 
bilateral relations soured over the crisis in East Timor, the 
nations conducted joint military exercises and were partners in a 
security treaty, now suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian soldiers are formally allowed to remain in East Timor  
until the national parliament ratifies the province's secession 
later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	But the two remaining infantry battalions are restricted to the  
capital Dili, where they are barricaded inside government 
buildings. Their commander last week gave a ``100 percent 
guarantee'' that there were no Kopassus left in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a botched militia ambush on Wednesday of a convoy of  
peacekeepers in the southwest of East Timor bore the ``unmistakable 
imprint'' of a special forces operation, said a peacekeeping 
officer who spoke on condition of anonymity on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two militiamen were killed and two Australian peacekeepers were  
slightly wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Assault rifles retrieved from the dead militiamen were both  
Indonesian army weapons: the Russian-built SKS, which has been 
phased out of service, and the Belgian FN, which is the standard 
infantry weapon today. 
</P>
<P>
	They are not available to civilians and can be obtained only  
from the army. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian military spokesman Maj. Gen. Sudradjat denied any  
Kopassus involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, Deputy U.N. Spokesman Manuel de Alameda e Silver  
said he had no knowledge of details of the ambush or who was 
involved. ``But of course, any action that is aimed at undermining 
the efforts of the MNF (multinational force) to restore security is 
of concern,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopassus -- along with the army's secretive intelligence bureau --  
is accused of organizing, training and arming the militia gangs 
last year to act as a counterweight to the pro-independence 
Falintil rebels who have fought Indonesian rule since the 
occupation of East Timor in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaked Indonesian army records showed a massive special forces  
buildup in East Timor last year, when the first militia gangs were 
set up, according to the Australian Broadcasting Corp. and The 
Australian newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopassus forces have been accused of engineering civil unrest  
and violence, and human rights groups claim Kopassus troops 
conducted a reign of terror in East Timor during 24 years of 
Indonesian rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights organizations also have blamed them for kidnapping  
dozens of pro-democracy activists during last year's protests that 
led to the ouster of Indonesia's longtime dictator Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the unit has been among Indonesian troops  
participating in joint exercises with the U.S. military, despite a 
1992 ban on the training of Indonesia's armed forces imposed in 
reaction to the Southeast Asian country's poor human rights record. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials maintained the program was not  
covered by a law that bars Indonesian troops from taking part in a 
U.S. training program for foreign soldiers known as IMET. State and 
Defense department officials said the prohibition did not apply to 
the joint combined exercises carried out by the U.S. Pacific 
Command. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of the U.S. Congress have questioned the U.S.  
training of Kopassus soldiers and officers, who they say received 
instruction from U.S. special operations advisers in skills like 
psychological warfare and reconnaissance missions. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month the administration suspended further military  
cooperation and arms sales to Indonesia after its armed forces 
allegedly instigated the campaign of violence that followed a vote 
for independence on Aug. 30. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
